caption:
There was a time when my only exercise was running. I figured that because it was the fastest way to feel breathless, it was the most efficient form of exercise.

Look at this infographic, including the legend. ‚ÄúRT‚Äù stands for resistance training (‚Äùweight training‚Äù, or exercises targetting muscles) and ‚ÄúAT‚Äù stands for aerobic training (‚Äùcardio‚Äù).

Notice that of the 8 categories of exercise benefits, 7 can be obtained from resistance exercise. Only cardiorespiratory function is unique to aerobic training.

Resistance training is essential for strength and preventing age-related muscle and bone loss, yet many exercisers don‚Äôt do it. Hopefully infographics such as this one help people learn that resistance training is the most impactful use of their exercise time.

What barriers prevent you from doing resistance training, if any?

For the US, "Wearable technology (#1), strength training with free weights (#2), and outdoor activities (#5) remain within the top five fitness trends, whereas home exercise gyms reveal a downward trend (#13, compared with #2 last year)."

There's no surprise that interest in wearable tech is rising. My questions is how much the increasing interest in fitness trackers is from people who are already exercising regularly, people who end up increasing their physical activity/health practices as a result of the device, or people with aspirations of improving fitness but remain sedentary.

As a fitness professional, I'm happy to see that interest in strength training is increasing!

caption:
Pomelos are one of my favourite fruits. It is also known as a Chinese grapefruit. I prefer them over regular grapefruits because they are not bitter and less watery. They are in season now, so try it out while they are available!

What‚Äôs great about pomelos in general is how filling and nutritious they are while having a low calorie density. I like them as an alternative carbohydrate source to grains in a meal. 

People who aren‚Äôt familiar with pomelos are not sure how to prepare them, so these photos should help.

What's your favourite app or wearable that helps you live a healthier lifestyle?

I'm actually a fan of Apple Health. I use it to track my sleep and steps. Women can also track menstrual cycle and related symptoms, which is helpful. Apple Health also integrates with many other apps/wearables so you can see your data on a single platform.

More recently, the sharing feature allows me to monitor my parents' data, including data related to risk of falls.

The data scientist in me wishes their interface had more data visualization and analysis features, but it's still pretty good for built-in free app.

#datascience #datavisualization #health

Gamify your goals

Duolingo was one of the pioneers in the gamification space. I started using it last year to improve my Chinese and French. For me, the app's most powerful feature is its streak count because:

1. I don't want to miss a day of lessons because I'll lose my streak.

2. At the same time, I have 1 or 2  banked "streak freezes" so I can keep my streak even if I miss a day (you need to earn or purchase the streak freezes).

This approach is great because it is process-oriented (e.g. do this habit) rather than outcome-oriented (e.g. lose weight), which has been shown scientifically to be better for long term adherence.

You don't any app to "gamify" a habit you want to add. Crossing off days on a calendar will work equally if not better (the more this reminder is in plain sight, the better). If you like crossing items off a to-do list, add the habit there (I love Asana and Notion for managing tasks).

What gamification strategies do you have?

I just lost my 170+ day Duolingo streak because I missed my lesson on New Year's Eve of all days. I guess the new year really IS a fresh start for me.

#datascience
üíõ

With power comes responsibility.

In the fitness space, people get excited about how AI can analyze movement, but what I am most excited about is how to use AI to help people adopt healthier lifestyles--we generally know it's important to exercise, but doing it is challenging.

If Netflix and YouTube can recommend content you'll find interesting, how can a health app recommend a health practice that you'll adopt to improve your health long term?

The recommendation will likely need to account for and adapt to your preferences, personality, knowledge/skills, and life stage. It also must be the right level of difficulty: If it's too challenging, you'll get discouraged and give up. If it's too easy, you might not get much benefit or lose motivation.

What application of AI are you most excited about? 

@aiforgood_foundation

caption:
There are already apps that do what personal trainers do: Creating goal-specific exercise programs, providing exercise demos, and even checking form. Will it put trainers out of work? 
No; here‚Äôs why:
1. The main challenges in fitness relate to getting people to adopt resistance training and continue long term, not simply knowing what to do. A good trainer doesn‚Äôt just check form; they help people DO the things that are aligned with their motivations and abilities.

2. Even when computer vision becomes advanced enough to distinguish between subtle differences in exercise technique, differences in muscle activation patterns (which can make the difference between pain vs. no pain) cannot always be be seen, even by an expert coach. A good movement coach knows the right questions and cues to use for the individual in front of them.

What WILL happen is that these AI-based fitness products will:

- Allow more people to exercise smarter.

- Weed out low quality exercise professionals and force remaining ones to up their standards.

- Make it easier for exercisers and fitness professionals to make data-informed decisions through easier data tracking and visualization.

What do you think?

In 2021 I got the audiobook Weapons of Math Destruction by Cathy O‚ÄôNeil after joining a book club for women in STEM. It discusses the dangers of artificial intelligence algorithms in perpetuating social inequalities. I had no idea at the time that I would embark on a career where I would be developing AI algorithms. I‚Äôll be relistening to this book, this time with the perspective of a data scientist.

caption:
Why walking or cardio are important, but not enough to keep you fit.

Lifting weights and resistance training are not just just for athletes or people who want to change their appearance; it helps to:

- Increase strength. That way, you can do everyday activities more easily with less pain/injury.
- Counteract muscle imbalances. Most sports and cardio activities (e.g. running, cycling, hiking) inherently train some muscles and not others. A good resistance training program systematically targets the various parts of the body to help you maintain good posture and reduce aches/pains.
- It counteracts the effects of ageing: Falls, broken hips, frailty, and stooped posture should not be accepted as inevitable.

Have questions or want to discuss? Comment below as this is a topic I‚Äôm passionate about.

caption:
There‚Äôs an abundance of free training resources out there, so why bother paying for it? 

The way I see it, my role is to apply my years of specialized education and experience to save people the guess work so they can just do the best bang-for-buck workouts AND still have time for other things. Online training can never replace in-person coaching, but I strive to provide the same professional guidance online as I do in person. That‚Äôs why I started making exercise videos. 

Julie* represents the type of client I most want to help: She has a high-stress career AND has 3 kids including a toddler. ‚ÄúI feel stronger, and more confident taking care of my baby daughter. I like the program you designed for me: it fits the tight time schedule I have, and I can always extend them when I have time (do 3 sets instead of 2). As the program stands now, I don't feel too pressured for time, and thus less stressed.‚Äù

Julie has made progress despite having little time to herself, being glued to her computer all day, and training with just a 12 kg kettlebell, 2x3kg dumbbells, and some bands. This is because:
- Exercise sessions take as little as 10 minutes per day.
- The exercises in her program provide high return-on-investment. 
- We constantly discuss how she can improve her sleep, nutrition, and recovery habits.

The deadlift with two bands is one such exercise in Julie‚Äôs program. It works many muscles, including muscles that help her improve her low back pain. All you need is 2 bands and an anchor (these are from Amazon).

What do you do to take care of your body when you are short on time and energy? Comment below!

* Name changed.

caption:
Performance doesn‚Äôt improve linearly, so persistence is key to make progress. 

It felt like I had regressed with my hand balancing skills. I took a week off of handstands practice to reduce fatigue before my Olympic lifting competition, and that allowed an improvement in hand balancing to finally reveal itself. 

People are surprised that there is such thing as a handstands class. You have to try it to understand the difficulty and variations. I had a  revelation just this week about how to better stabilize with the core ‚Äîtensing the right places, the right amount, at the right time. 

What skill are you working on? It could be an instrument, dance, or sport.

caption:
Get Over the Fear: How to Do Your First Handstand Hold
¬†
The wall-facing handstand is basically an advanced plank! It does emphasize shoulder stability more than the standard plank.
¬†
These are the benefits of handstands, even if you have a desk job:
‚Ä¢ They train your core and glutes to support a healthy back.
‚Ä¢ They help you maintain good posture: To do a handstand, you need adequate overhead mobility and thoracic mobility, which we don't tend to challenge enough in our day to day activities (use it or lose it!).
‚Ä¢ They strengthen the muscles that help improve posture and keep your shoulders pain-free, such as the rotator cuff, serratus anterior, and lower trapezius.
¬†
Steps:
1. Keep your abs tight as you walk your hands and feet up into the handstand position.
2. As you hold, push the floor away from to keep your shoulder muscles active.
3. Ensure good core stability by keeping your ribs pulled towards your spine. In other words, maintain a good hollow body position. The muscles of the butt and front of the thighs should also be tense, not just the upper body and core.
4. While the goal is to bring your hands as close to the wall as you can, start in a more horizontal position if needed and gradually work towards a more vertical position as you improve strength and stability.
Whatever position you choose, always push the floor away and keep your ribs pulled towards your spine.
¬†
If you give this a try, leave a comment on how this goes for you.

caption:
It's a new year. The time when the fitness industry likes to guilt you into buying their products and services. Or get you "motivated" to make a grand transformation by crushing yourself.
¬†
The reality is that for most people who struggle with fitness on top of career, family, and social life, this type of mindset does not lead to long lasting health change.
¬†
Here's what will work for these people:
‚úîÔ∏èApproaching health and exercise with incremental sustainable changes instead of going all-in or not bothering at all. If you're a type-A personality, I know this is hard!
‚úîÔ∏èInstead thinking that a lack of "motivation" is what's stopping them, they take a small step that provides evidence they are capable of making the change. You don't need motivation for action; motivation can come AFTER action. It can literally be one squat. 
¬†
Working out at home is not fun (especially in a cold garage). I never feel "motivated" to train. But every day, I reluctantly start training by massaging my shoulder with the lacrosse ball before going onto the next exercise. I tell myself that I don't have to finish the prescribed sets and reps (though I usually do), as long as I get SOMETHING done. I don't train to "transform" my body, but to take care of it, to practice challenging skills, and to feel happy about the physical feats I can do.¬†And while I'll never have a huge social media following, I hope I can be relatable to the average working adult who would otherwise not bother training their muscles.
¬†
Do you feel guilty about your health habits? Could you reframe the situation to help you feel good about what you're doing well, or to help you move closer to your goals?

caption:
How to Make Progress with Home Workouts: 4 Push Up Exercise Variations

As you get better at push ups, eventually you'd need to do way too many reps to get a good training effect. I'm all about being time-efficient, so instead of doing endless reps of the standard push up, here are 4 push up progressions that will help you get stronger and gain muscle while saving time:
üëâDecline push up
üëâBanded decline push up
üëâDeficit decline push up
üëâBanded deficit decline push up
¬†
In addition to saving time, you'll be leveraging science and physics with these push up variations that you can do at home without equipment aside from stuff around the house!
‚úîÔ∏èElevating the feet shifts more of your bodyweight to your upper body.
‚úîÔ∏èThe band provides additional resistance, but even better is that it is an accommodating resistance. In other words, it adds more weight in the positions where you are stronger so you are challenged uniformly throughout the movement (otherwise, it gets very easy as you reach the top).
‚úîÔ∏èElevating the hands as shown allows you to descend lower relative to the hands. Using a greater motion enhances muscle growth.

Will you give any of these a try? Let me know how it goes!

Why the scale goes crazy during the holidays: part 3/3.
¬†
Aside from holiday noms, some other things that increase scale weight that aren't due to fat gain include:
- Water retention during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle (i.e. the days before the period starts).
- Water retention due to stress. If you're a little less stressed now, you may even find the scale goes down!
- Water retention from certain medications.
¬†
This year has been my best year yet as stress has been at an all-time low, which has helped my body get objectively healthier (as confirmed with lab tests) despite no longer sticking with "clean" eating and putting on body fat. Did you learn something from this series? Any more questions? Comment below!

Why the scale goes crazy during the holidays: part 2/3.
¬†
It takes a surplus or deficit of ~3500 calories to gain or lose a pound of fat, which is more than what your average person consumes on an average day. Here are some explanations for large weight fluctuations that have nothing to do with true fat or muscle changes, but rather to do eating differently than normal during celebrations:
- Higher food residue in the digestive tract due to higher fibre intake.
- If you're constipated due to eating stuff you're not used to (like we did at the Indian buffet pictured), the food remaining in your gut will also add weight.
- Less time between the last meal and when you weigh yourself from late night eating.
¬†
What's the largest weight fluctuation you've experienced from one day to another, and why did that happen? I once did some targeted food, hydration, and salt manipulation to reduce my scale weight by 3 kg in 1 week for a lifting competition. It had nothing to do with fat loss.
¬†
In part 3, I'll go over some reasons for weight fluctuations that are neither due to fat gain nor diet.

Why the scale goes crazy during the holidays: part 1/3.
¬†
Do you get emotional (or simply curious) about the number on the scale fluctuating a couple (or more) pounds day to day?
¬†
It takes a surplus or deficit of ~3500 calories to gain or lose a pound of fat, which is unlikely to happen from a day or two. When we eat much differently than usual (e.g. due to holiday festivities), here are some explanations for large weight fluctuations that have nothing to do with true fat or muscle changes:
- Water retention due to higher salt intake than normal.
- Muscles being fuller with glycogen and water, e.g. due to higher carbohydrate intake. For every gram of carbohydrate stored in the muscle (glycogen), we store 3-4 g of water.
¬†
I'm super grateful to be able to reconnect with with friends over food. In part 2, I'll cover some additional factors that make that scale weight spike up. Did anything in this post surprise you?

¬†
Stretching and mobility exercises can help, but ultimately, having well-functioning postural muscles is what will hold you up in the proper position. So if you're strapped for time, why not kill two birds with one stone: Get stronger AND improve posture/mobility.
¬†
¬†In this hands-on workshop I'll be presenting tomorrow for @scwist.canada , busy professionals will learn what to prioritize in their exercise routine to improve posture and reduce pain. You will also gain practical strategies on how to include strength training in your life, even if it is just one minute at a time.
¬†
‚Ä¢ Have confidence to exercise regularly.
‚Ä¢ Get stronger so you can perform better in your everyday life.

caption:
In my old job, I had a lot of patients who were healthcare workers with back injuries. Last year, I took a course aimed at teaching healthcare assistants how to do safe patient transfers. I wanted to better understand the training that healthcare workers receive.
¬†
This type of course is extremely important, but a few things frustrated me about how back safety was framed in this course:
1. It gave the impression that tasks are dangerous and that the back is fragile.
2. There was NO discussion whatsoever about how strengthening the back muscles is protective of back injury.
¬†
I don't blame the school. They were communicating the same information that is given by WorkSafeBC and other authorities.
¬†
I messaged the instructor to invite further discussion about these frustrations. Unfortunately, the discussion did not go beyond her replying that she'd read the link I sent later on. I gave her my email but I have never heard back and I have no way of communicating with her now that the course is done.
¬†
I decided to present on back health at @safecarebc‚Äôs Hearts and Hands Conference that's happening next week. I'm hoping to shake up how we talk about back health and help empower more people through principles of strength training and resistance exercise.

#careaide #healthcareworker #healthcare #nurse #ohs #occupationalhealth #healthandsafety

Having a well functioning core is important for low back health and since the core stabilizes your lumbar spine and helps with posture. And of course, if training the 6 pack helps you feel confident at the beach, that doesn't hurt either.
¬†
Unfortunately, conventional crunches and sit ups put pressure on the lumbar discs, which can be problematic for those with discogenic back pain. Even worse is that they often train the hip flexors more than the abdominals, which means¬†you're wasting time.
¬†
The McGill curl up was created by the world's top scientist on low back pain, Dr Stuart McGill. Based on his lab research, this is the smarter way to train the core, particularly the rectus abdominus (6 pack muscles).

@squat_university recommends starting with sets of 5 reps with 10 sec holds to enhance spine stability. 
¬†
If you primarily want to BUILD the 6 pack muscles for aesthetics and not just improve core stability, it seems that isotonic exercises rather than isometrics (e.g. movement-based vs. holds) are better. In that case, consider doing the curl ups for as many reps as you can to really feel a burn in the abs. Take a short rest and repeat for several sets--rest interval should be equal or shorter than work interval. An example can be to do as many controlled reps as possible for 30 sec, rest 20 sec, then repeat for 3-5 rounds. You want to feel as much burn as possible to enhance muscle growth. However, keep in mind that no matter how much you train the abs, having a 6 pack requires your abdominal fat to be low enough for the ab lines to show.

Do you enjoy training the core? Why or why not? Personally, I don't enjoy exercises where I don't feel like I am accomplishing anything, which is why I prefer lifting weights, handstands, and pull ups!

Today I attended a panel discussion by @scwist.canada on barriers for women in STEM careers. As a kinesiologist, my mission is to promote strength training. Unfortunately, cultural attitudes and beliefs about strength training have stopped a lot of women from strength training. This is particularly true in non-Western cultures, where lifting weights is considered for men or bodybuilders only.
¬†
I'm participating in ‚ÄúI Move for Immigrant Women in Science‚Äù, an initiative by the @IWS_Network. In line with my passion for promoting strength training, I suggest that next time you go for a walk, consider doing a few lunges--even 2 lunges will be good to start. You'll not only still enjoy the benefits of being outside, but also strengthen your bones and muscles to keep your back and knees healthy. Swipe for technique tips!
¬†
Personally, my mom calls me a man because I lift heavy weights, whereas my dad has not made any such comments and has even built me a platform so I can do Olympic lifting in my garage.
¬†
What prevents you from doing strength training, if anything?¬†

caption:
Pull ups with bands are NOT the best way to get your first pull up.
¬†
Being able to get your first pull up is a great goal, but getting from zero to 1 pull up is not intuitive. Today I (somewhat) hit a personal record in the pull up--6 reps. Notice that I got the chin over the bar on the first few reps, but on the 6th, I struggled hard and was not able to pull up as high.
¬†
I have never used bands or the assisted pull up machine for my pull up training and have continued to make progress. So why not use bands? Bands provide a ton of assistance at the bottom position but provide almost no assistance as you reach the top, which is the hardest part of the movement.
¬†
Here's a better way to work towards a full pull up: Start with just eccentric (aka "negative") chin ups (pull up with underhand grip). Climb up and start with the bar at the chest, then lower down slowly until you reach a full hang. To train towards your first pull up, aim to increase the duration of each lower to 30 seconds. At that point, you'll likely be able to get your first chin up.
¬†
If you do this right, you'll feel your abs burn--it's actually better for activating the abs than most ab exercises. 

Are you working towards your first pull up, or improving your pull-ups? 
Send me a message or tag me in your post if you‚Äôd like a form check!

caption:
#STEM - Strength Training and #Ergonomics Minute
¬†
No amount of activity can counteract the effects of being sedentary for 8 hours. Ideally, you would avoid being in a static position for more than 20 minutes at a time. So what if you have to work at a desk all day? Here's an exercise you can do right at your desk, not only to avoid being static for too long, but to actually improve your posture and shoulder health. All you need is about 30 seconds.
¬†
This is a great exercise to train the lower trapezius and serratus anterior, which are both involved in upward rotation of the scapula--super important if you want to maintain overhead mobility of the shoulders, avoid shoulder pain, and have good upper body strength (especially for overhead movements).
¬†
The science:
üëâCreating external rotation torque by pushing against the band will decrease subscapularis involvement while activating the teres minor and infraspinatus.
üëâPulling the elbows into the body will decrease posterior deltoid involvement.
üëâDepressing the shoulders will decrease upper trap involvement.
¬†
If you do this as part of your workday, perform 5-12 quality repetitions up to 5 times throughout day, approximately every 30-120 minutes--the quality of each rep is more important than how many you do. Perhaps anchor it to another daily event, such as when checking email, waiting for a meeting to start, or going to the bathroom. 

Of course, this is also a great exercise to do outside of work to keep your shoulders healthy. You can include it as part of a warm up before resistance training or while resting between heavier exercises.
‚Ä¢

caption:
#STEM - Strength Training and #Ergonomics Minute!
¬†
There are several reasons why inverted rows (aka TRX rows, ring rows, suspension trainer rows, bodyweight rows) stand out:
¬†
üëâCompared to some other row variations, it puts negligible strain on the low back--great if you have low back pain.
üëâGreat as part of minimalist, time-efficient home workouts or travel workouts as the equipment is inexpensive, easy to pack, and allows for endless exercise options for the entire body.
üëâYou can vary the difficulty even with only one piece of equipment.
üëâThe demands of the movement compliment the strength curve of the muscles, i.e. the movement is hardest at your strongest position and easiest at your weakest position so the muscles get trained uniformly along the entire range of motion. Contrast this with rows using a band, which become heavier as the band stretches and become hardest at your weakest position.
üëâHelps improve posture, improve shoulder health, and strengthen the core.‚Ä¢

#STEM :¬†Strength Training and Ergonomics Minute
¬†
Getting bodywork done by a therapist or masseuse is great to keep your body feeling good, but most of us don't have the time or money to get it done weekly, if at all.
¬†
Sitting or slouching means the thoracic spine (between the neck and low back) gets stuck in this hunched position, which can cause the back, neck, and shoulders to not feel great. Here's a no-equipment way to mobilize the thoracic spine.
¬†
When reaching the elbow to the ceiling, use the other arm to push to assist with increasing rotation. When you reach the end, inhale, then exhale and push further into rotation.
When reaching the elbow under the armpit, try to get the elbow to get as close to the floor as possible. The supporting arm should continue to push the floor throughout.

caption:
Home/Office Functional Training: Core Training without Crunches!
¬†
Did you know that push ups are a core exercise when done properly? That's because the abs have to work to keep your low back from sagging down. In the elevated single arm push up, you will also train another SUPER important function of the core: the ability to resist rotation.
¬†
1. Stand close to a wall or elevated surface with a wide stance. 
2. Place hand below chest height or lower (lower will be harder).
3. Go onto your tip toes. 
4. Lower the body until shoulders pass the wall, then push back up. 
¬†
Tips:
- Keep the muscles in the abs, glutes, and even the front of the legs tight to keep the body in a stable straight line from head to toe, which allows your body to express its full strength.
- Forearm should remain approximately horizontal. Adjust hand and/or feet position if needed to achieve this.
- Don't let the body rotate. Widen the stance to make this easier.

caption:
Is it truly heavy, or does it just FEEL heavy?
¬†
My dad's been a champ. I train him in person briefly every few weeks but he mostly trains on his own following the simple program I created for him on the online training app (his preferred workout time is 10pm!). After checking his form using the usual weight he uses, I said it was time to switch to the heaviest band. He didn't think he could do it, but I told him he could, even for 1 rep. He managed to get 2 sets of 10 and 12 reps with the heaviest band!
¬†
If you are worried about getting hurt and haven't received much coaching from a trainer, it's likely you're underestimating your strength. In my experience training hundreds of people, people can double or triple the weight they're using for lower body movements like goblet squats and deadlifts.
¬†
Today I did squats, and I knew I was pushing my limit because there was a point when I almost stopped moving, not simply because it "felt" hard. My first trainer, @lift4love23, taught me how to push beyond what I was capable of and as a result, I saw some rapid progress that time.
¬†
Erring on the side of caution is a good idea when you're training on your own, but even just a bit of feedback from a trainer can ensure you're not missing out on potential strength gains.
¬†
Have you been surprised by your own strength?

Do you ever feel pinching or pain in your shoulders, particularly when reaching overhead?
¬†
With our modern world of sitting, computer work, and stress, our shoulders can suffer. 
¬†
Even though the anatomy text books list the function of the serratus anterior as simply protraction, we can get better activation of this muscle by reducing involvement of other muscles which may take over to compensate:
1. Positioning the arms above shoulder height will reduce anterior deltoid involvement.
2. Creating external rotation torque will reduce pectoralis and subscapularis involvement.
3. Depressing the shoulders will decrease upper trap involvement.
¬†
If you're doing other exercises like push ups or planks, you can incorporate these strategies to better train the serratus anterior.
¬†
Here's a serratus anterior exercise that incorporates these strategies:
1. Get on all fours to get into the start position.
2. Position the hands a few inches in front of the shoulders.
¬†3. Sink your chest into the floor to retract the shoulder blades (this will cause the back to arch). This is the start position.
¬†4. Push the floor away from you as hard as you can (this will cause the upper back and shoulders to round). As you do so, imagine screwing the hands outwards, as if trying to turn the right hand clockwise and the left hand counter clockwise. Even though the hands won't move due to the friction of the floor, this will activate the serratus anterior muscles more.
¬†5. Release and return to the start position. Keep the shoulders far from your ears--do not allow the shoulders to shrug as you push.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
Today is National Health and Fitness Day in Canada.
¬†
I am a personal trainer, yet I still have my own personal trainer, @coachjure the "No BS Strength Coach" (true to name). I believe one of the most impactful things you can do for your health and fitness is to invest in professional guidance, whether that be long term or just for a few weeks to get you started on the right path.
¬†
It warms my heart to get positive feedback from my clients. But to be honest, my style of coaching does not suit everyone. As much as I wish I could be, I will never be the fun trainer who will make you laugh like @matty__porter or @robertnels, or have the perfect waist to hip ratio like @iris.salihagic, and that weakness is precisely what makes me much better at coaching clients online. The clients who appreciate my style the most are the ones who do the work simply with a bit of guidance and who value strength and proper form, not simply having fun or crushing "workouts". They appreciate the careful planning I put into their custom programs and the detailed feedback I give when they send me videos of them doing an exercise.
¬†
Hiring a trainer/coach is a big investment, so to get the most out of the experience, you need to think about what you want/need and communicate that clearly. At the same time, be aware that the role of a good coach is to challenge you and show you what you need‚Äîeven if it's not what you want. In my case, @coachjure very bluntly told me I was using too little weight on hip thrusts, and 3 days ago I discovered that I was able to add at least 20 kg more--from 45 to 65 kg for 12 reps. My glutes are still recovering.
¬†
What do YOU need to stay engaged with your fitness? Is it to be social while exercising? Is it to feel sweaty? Is it to feel a sense of achievement?
¬†

caption:
Split Squat from Kneeling.
¬†
The lunge is an important fundamental movement pattern. Starting it from the kneeling position is not only a great starting point to learn it, but also a great way to assess your movement quality.
¬†
Start in a half kneeling position:
- Back thigh and torso completely vertical.
- Toes of back foot tucked so they contact the floor.
- Front leg bent 90 degrees at the knee with shin completely vertical and foot flat on the floor.
Stand up so that both knees are straight.
Lower back down to the start position and repeat.

caption:
Lat pulldown in quadruped position.
¬†
This exercise is harder than it looks. Give it a try and let me know how it goes!
¬†
Benefits of this exercise:
- Train the pull up movement from home without a pull up bar.
- Core stability.
- Shoulder stability of the supporting arm.
¬†
Technique tips:
- Keep the spine neutral so that core is engaged; don't let the belly sag down.
- Push the floor away with the supporting arm to keep the shoulder in a strong position.
- Keep the rest of the body motionless as you pull the moving arm. Get the core to work!
- Move the shoulder through its full range of motion. When the arm is straight in the forward position, allow the shoulder come towards the ears. When you initiate the pull, pull the shoulder blade away from the ear, then pull the elbow to your side.

Test time! How strong and stable are your hips?
¬†
Here's a test of not only balance, but how well your GLUTEUS MEDIUS muscles function. These muscles function to keep your pelvis level any time you stand on one leg, including when you walk and run.
¬†
This test of hip stability is called the Trendelenburg test:
1. Stand with your hands on your hips to help you feel/visualize movement of the pelvis.
2. Bring one knee up to hip height and hold it there for 3 seconds. Repeat on the other side for 3 reps total.
4. Repeat for 2 reps per side. A little bit of weight shift side to side is expected.
¬†
Common faults:
A. Positive Trendelenburg sign: Hip drop on lifted side.
B. Modified Trendelenburg sign: Excessive rising of the hip on the lifted side OR torso leaning away from the lifted side.
C. Loss of balance.
¬†
When the gluteus medius doesn't work well, it can mean:
- The pelvis won't be stabilized as well. Because the low back is connected to the pelvis, this can lead to low back pain.
- The knees will be poorly aligned during movements such as squats and lunges.
- Excessive wear and tear on joints such as the spine, hip, and knee, which can lead to pain.
¬†
Try it out and let me know in the comments if you:
1. Had a perfect test!
2. Had one of the faults listed above. If so, which one?

caption:
Isometric single arm row with a towel.
¬†
As I've written about so many times, the row is a fundamental exercise that should be in every good strength training program: It helps you improve your posture by training the upper back muscles that hold your shoulders and upper spine in good position. Performing it isometrically using a towel is a great no-equipment option. Isometric exercises (where the muscles are working even when the joints remain fixed) are scientifically shown to:
- Increase strength even without weights/machines.
- Have a painkilling effect for the involved structures.
- Allow for maximal effort with less risk than with traditional strength training.
¬†
Tips:
Make sure you feel the muscles on the back of and in between your shoulder blades working, not just your biceps/arms.
You should not feel any tension in your upper traps or on the front of your shoulders. If you do, pull shoulder blades down and back with each pull.
Avoid holding your breath so blood pressure doesn't get too high.
¬†
Let me know how it goes if you give a try!

caption:
Shoulder issues are so common: Whether it's the inability to reach overhead, pinching or pain with certain arm movements, or "frozen shoulder" (which I saw in so many female care aides and housekeeping staff), weak shoulder muscles affect people of all ages and fitness levels.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
The push up is a strength exercise that doesn't require equipment, but doing them without balancing them out with other exercises can make our shoulders and posture worse than they already are. Here's an exercise requiring no equipment that helps keep you improve posture and keep the shoulders pain-free.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Prone "T" exercise: 
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢1. Lie on your stomach with your head resting on the floor and arms out to the side in a "T" shape". 
2. Pull your shoulders away from the floor and away from your ears (at the end of the video, I show what this looks like when performed upright).
3. While keeping your shoulder blades in that position, lift your arms off the floor and hold. Keep the arms in line with the shoulder (don't let them drift towards the body) and shoulders away from the ears (not shrugged).
4. Hold for 10 seconds for 6-10 reps. Feel the muscles in between and on the surface of the shoulder blade activate. For more challenge, perform while holding 1-3lb weights.
‚Ä¢

Having good posture and shoulder health in the modern world requires us to train upper body pulling movements such as rows, but what if you don't have any gym equipment and aren't strong enough to do a pull up? The reverse plank can be done without any gym equipment.
¬†
Tips:
- This can be done for reps and/or as a hold for time. 
- Pull the shoulders and elbows back to hold the position and you'll feel the muscles on the back of the shoulder and between the shoulder blades working. 
- You will also be using the muscles on the back of the thighs and glutes. Keep the low back flat (tailbone tucked down) to avoid feeling pressure in the low back (feel abs and glutes work to do this).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Prone Y (more advanced than the prone T)

In our modern world, certain muscles require more attention to counteract all the sitting and desk work we do.

If you have trouble feeling your upper back muscles working when doing things like rows and pull ups, this exercise can wake them up and help your shoulders move better and improve your posture.

1. Lie on your stomach with your head resting on the floor and arms reached forward in a Y shape (about 45 deg angle from the head).
2. Reach arms forward as high as you can, shrugging the shoulders.
3. Pull your shoulders away from the floor and away from your ears.
4. While keeping your shoulder blades in that position, lift your arms off the floor and hold. It is more important to keep the upper arms reached forward than to lift the arms high.
5. Hold for 10 seconds for 6-10 reps. Feel the muscles in between and on the surface of the shoulder blade activate. For more challenge, perform while holding 1-3lb weights.

Lunges are a foundational movement pattern, but they can be challenging to start with due to coordination and even due to muscle tightness in the front of the thigh/hip (super common!). Here's a variation that is a great starting point and also trains lower body strength to get up and down from the floor without using the arms.
¬†
Key points:
- Keep the hip, knee, and ankle of the front foot aligned when viewed from the front.
- Imagine pushing that front foot into the floor to get up.
- Descend with control to enhance strength improvement.
- Progress by holding weight. If you really want to challenge your stability and have the ability, perform it while holding a weight overhead!

caption:
Silvia's Cycling Stories.
¬†
The sunglasses I wore during yesterday's cycling adventure broke while I carried them in my fanny pack. Normally I buy sunglasses from the drug store, but these were the double-polarized ones the eye doctor recommended after my laser eye surgery, so went to the post office to send them for repair even though shipping costs 2-3x the cost of a new pair from London Drugs. I used this post office trip to practise making hand signals while on the bike and managed to make a 1-sec turn signal at some of my turns. Still need to figure out how to signal while pedalling without losing control of the bike.
¬†
Also picked up some Zevia which was on sale.

Last year I learned to ride a bike and my first big bike trip was 30 min to QE Park. I wasn't able to pedal fast enough to keep my bike moving up the hill, so had to get off and walk. Today was my first time biking outside all year. This time, I pedalled up the hill and only stopped at the top to cross the street. So I took the chance to take a commemorative selfie. Also had my first ice cream of the year.

On the first couple days of learning to bike, I thought it was impossible. On day 2, my abs felt tired from stiffening up to stabilize. The only reason I persisted is that if people with worse coordination than me can do it, I should be able to also. After 7 straight days of practice, I was able to bike (with relaxed abs)!

My clients often get frustrated when they can't get certain exercises right initially. If you're experiencing the same thing, just know that it's normal and that with deliberate practice, the body will learn and improve just like how I learned to bike. I still need practice to learn to make turn signals without losing control of the bike.

"How many reps should I do?"
¬†
It depends. If your goal is to be able to have the endurance to perform an action for several repetitions, such as bending over when giving your baby a bath, then using lighter weight performed with higher reps would improve that.
¬†
If your goal is to be able to increase how much weight you can lift, such as being able to move a couch or compete in max lifting, then you'll have to use lower reps to increase how much weight you can lift.
¬†
Long term, you want to train both low, moderate, and high repetitions to improve both muscular endurance, strength, and growth. A good fitness coach can help you plan the right program for you.
¬†
Are you guilty of only training a certain number of reps?

Believe it or not, one of my rituals before a heavy Olympic lift is an exercise I often recommend to improve posture and counteract long periods of desk work (no, not twerking).
¬†
Can you guess what it is? It does not involve any weight at all. See the second video for the full exercise demonstration.
¬†
It's an exercise called the wall angel, which involves standing with your back against a wall and sliding your arms overhead while keeping the arms in contact with the wall. The same motion can also be done without the wall (but the wall lets you know if you're cheating). This exercise requires several things which help promote good posture and shoulder function (which is why I do in preparation to catch a heavy weight overhead):
- Thoracic extension.
- Shoulder retraction.
- Upward rotation of the scapula.
- Overhead reaching.
¬†
Are you able to keep the arms on the wall while reaching straight overhead without arching the low back? Try it out and comment below!

caption:
Striving to be the best has a cost, and sometimes it‚Äôs not worth it.
¬†
Back when I was competing in Olympic lifting in 2016-2018, I had big ambitions for my sport performance. Being the typical Type A personality, sport performance consumed my thoughts. It was not rational because some of the things I did (e.g. sacrificing sleep to train, undereating to keep bodyweight low) ultimately costed me my health and thus limited my performance despite all those hours training and thinking about nutrition. Sadly, I chose this hobby over my work.
¬†
Tomorrow is my first @bcweightlifting competition since 2018. My mindset towards training is different these days. I place more importance on helping others get stronger and healthier AND still achieve their career goals. My results in Olympic lifting don't indicate my value as a person. No one cares how much I lift. I'll never be a Type B personality, but have definitely moved closer towards it, and this has helped my well-being.
¬†
Are you a Type A personality? Can you relate to how this is not always a good thing?

caption:
Hangin' out!

For those with desk jobs, hanging has many benefits that can be explained with #science:
- It can improve your posture by mobilizing body parts that often get tight with sitting (e.g. pecs, lats, thoracic spine).
- It decompresses the low back, specifically the discs. These discs get compressed when you sit for a long time, which can lead to problems. For some people with back pain, this decompression can provide relief.
- It strengthens your grip and shoulders (including your rotator cuff muscles).
- It's FUN! Tap into your inner child.

Where do you like to hang (literally)? Would you feel comfortable hanging at your workplace to break up periods of sitting?

Is it better to rest or exercise a bad back?

Part 5

Back pain affects those with physical jobs AND those with desk jobs. When you feel limited in what you can do, that negatively impacts your mental state, which ultimately contributes to more pain.

Instead of thinking about the pain what you CAN'T do, seek to improve what you CAN do. Even if pain level stays the same, you are making progress if you are able to DO more without worsening your condition.

Not sure what options are safe for you? Seek help from a qualified exercise professional or physiotherapist.

What activities give you a self of achievement? For me, it's lifting heavy things, or in this case, pulling my bodyweight up!

Part 4

Back pain affects those with physical jobs AND those with desk jobs. Here is some thing to consider: Exercise changes the entire physiology of the body both short- and long-term, including reduce chronic inflammation and pain. While some rest or reduced activity may be needed initially, staying sedentary for extended periods will worsen not just your health, but could make the pain persist. Find a form of exercise that doesn't aggravate your symptoms and your body will thank you.

Is it better to rest or exercise a bad back?

Part 3

Fix your position and make low back pain go away.

People will often blame certain exercises for causing pain, but sometimes the issue is how they are executing the movement rather than the actual exercise.

Push ups were all the rage at the start of the pandemic. Unfortunately, most people doing push ups are not getting the full benefit of them (including some really strong/buff people). Did you know the push up also engages the abs and glutes when done properly?

When you let the low back arch, you're not engaging the abs and glutes. This arched back can cause low back discomfort during the push up and other movements/exercises.

If you like to think about science, there's a good chance you spend a lot of time thinking. This is good in many situations, but can get in the way because you it allows fear/anxiety to get in the way of what you're capable of.

Today I did squats, and my fear of the weight almost stopped me. I started my first warm up set with 16 kg less than my goal weight for the day. It felt heavy and I was nervous. I added 10 kg. It felt heavier. I doubted my ability. Added another 3 kg, which was still 3kg lighter than the goal weight. I got more nervous, but focused on key points for proper set up and execution. In the end, I managed to do 4 sets at the goal weight.

Even when it feels tough, you are likely capable of much more. I don't like discomfort and avoid risk. My first personal trainer taught me how to push when the weight feels heavy, but it's still something I struggle with.

Do you get paralysis by analysis? When did you last surprise yourself with what you could do by pushing out of your comfort zone?

My long term goal is to promote movement/exercise as medicine on a larger scale.
The evidence shows that simply telling people what to do is not enough. Successful behaviour change is more likely if:
1. Barriers to change are reduced.
2. There is less uncertainty about what actions to take.
¬†
In this workshop, I kept these in mind by providing just a few exercises that can be done at work in <30sec. When employers such as @kaianalytics invest in the wellbeing of their staff through at-work activities (such as this workshop we did last week), not only do staff get the resources to keep their bodies feeling better, but are more likely to actually IMPLEMENT these things because they don't have to find the time to do it on their own outside work hours.
¬†
What does your organization do to keep your team members' bodies feeling good, and how do you make sure the staff are ACTUALLY taking advantage of these wellness perks?

@ugniawoo has a full schedule working in medical research while doing graduate studies. Needless to say, she needed a time-efficient training program to do from home. After a couple months of us working together, she was able to do full push ups for the first time! She was pleasantly surprised when I showed her this video.
¬†
Training for results requires patience and consistency. The science of motivation is shows that if you don‚Äôt enjoy the process and can't understand how the actions align with who you are, you are less likely to make exercise stick.
¬†
While doing the same exercise routine week to week did not provide the same entertainment as doing a different group fitness workout every time, seeing measurable progress was a reward in itself. Seeing the results of your consistency is also a daily reminder that you are acting in accordance to who you want to be.

caption:
How to increase your pull ups in 30 seconds.
¬†
Empty your bladder and take off your sweater. Less weight to lift, right?
¬†
Last week I got a personal record of 5 chin ups. Today was the day of my max chin up/pull up contest with @tak_lift and @fitnesswithryo and I was doubtful I would be able to add even 1 more rep. On the first set (2nd video), I surprised myself with 7 reps. I then did 200 reps of light leg isolation work, emptied my bladder, and got EIGHT reps on my next attempt (1st video).
¬†
3 days ago, I literally peed my pants doing a single pull up, as well as on a light front squat. It just goes to show that sometimes you can surprise yourself, and how you can have strong days and weak days. (Or maybe it was all those banded leg curls and leg extensions that @coachjure had me do that helped me get that extra chin up?!)
¬†
What's your craziest story of going from weak to strong (or vice-versa) in just a few days, and what do you think caused the big change?

caption:
How you can get 8000 steps per day with a desk job.
¬†
Strategy #2: Rain or shine, or even snow! Just dress appropriately.
¬†
I was tempted to skip my morning walk today, but reminded myself how important good sleep is. Two weeks ago, I accidentally discovered that I was able to fix my sleep problems after starting my day with a walk. Before, I would frequently wake up in the middle of the night and not be able to fall back asleep, which would cause me to feel lethargic and crave more food.
¬†
Here's the science: The exposure to natural daylight first thing in the morning helps us to calibrate our body clocks so that we can sleep well at night.

Learn to lift with the legs!
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
As much as I love Olympic weightlifting, which involves creating power with your lower body to generate momentum to lift a heavy weight over head, it is not where most people should start. However, there are kettlebell variations of the Olympic lifts that teach you how to move with high speed.

üèãÔ∏èThe double arm single kettlebell clean (or high pull to catch) is my go-to exercise to introduce someone to creating power with the legs. I have found that those with desk jobs tend to forget how to create power from their lower body (especially the glutes) and instead compensate with their low back and upper body when lifting.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢¬†
Tips:
üëâFirst, make sure you know how to perform a deadlift using primarily your lower body instead of feeling pressure in your low back.
Warm up with few reps of deadlifts using the kettlebell.
üëâThe lower body should initiate the lift powerfully from the floor. Imagine pushing the floor away from you to create more power, almost like you're about to jump.
üëâThe hands should grip the kettlebell lightly so they can slide along the handle.
üëâQuickly tuck the elbows into the sides of your body as you receive the kettlebell at chest height.
üëâIf you're doing it right, you should feel the glutes working hard with no pressure in the low back.
‚Ä¢

caption:
Not your typical social media midriff selfie from a fitness professional.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
I was once a young scientist (glasses and all!) measuring muscle activity on human volunteers. I spent hours in the lab to figure out equipment, run experiments, and process data. I did so much mouse clicking that I had to eventually switch to using the mouse with my left hand to avoid repetitive strain injuries.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
To be honest, I don't know if all those hours in the lab will ever have ANY positive contribution to science. After I finished my Masters degree, I spent months applying to research jobs, but didn't get a single offer. Looking back, this was a blessing. It caused me to think about how to best make use of my education. Not long after starting a job as a kinesiologist in a physiotherapy clinic, I felt grateful for being able to impact the health of individuals. After 4 years in the clinic, I realized that instead of helping people only AFTER they got injured, I wanted to help people stay injury-free, and that is why I switched to personal training.
‚Ä¢

caption:
Should you do more cardio if your goal is fat loss?
¬†
üö¥I've gotten into the habit lately of doing light cycling whenever I'm on a call that is not work-related. It's just another way to avoid being sedentary that doesn't require any thinking.
¬†
üëâOften when people want to lose fat, they think that adding cardio is the best way to go. This may work, but it also may NOT work long-term for some reasons:
- If the cardio exercise is fatiguing, your body may move less the rest of the day, thus cancelling out any energy deficit that the cardio may have created. Even if you spend 1 hour doing cardio, the remaining 23 hours a day will have a bigger impact on your total energy expenditure.
- Moderate-intensity cardio may increase appetite, so you may end up eating more. It's very easy to eat more calories than what you burn through exercise.
- Certain cardio activities like jogging/running make it harder to gain and maintain muscle mass.
¬†
üåàCardiovascular exercise is super beneficial for health, but for fat loss (especially if you're a time-crunched professional), consider these other things as the main part of your fat loss strategy:
‚úîÔ∏èNutrition. It takes a lot of work to burn 300 calories but all it takes is a fancy latte to consume it.
‚úîÔ∏èLight movement throughout the day (e.g. walking), which significantly impacts calorie burn without causing more fatigue or increasing appetite. The scientific term for this is non-exercise activity thermogenesis (NEAT). I actually consider my light cycling during phone calls to be a form of NEAT because i's like going for a walk, but on a bike.
‚úîÔ∏èResistance (weight) training to avoid muscle loss during weight loss. This helps you maintain your metabolic rate.
¬†‚Ä¢
If you want help with the above, now is your chance to get some professional guidance and accountability with it. How is your squat form?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
The squat is such a great exercise, but I am honestly surprised when I can see someone do it with good depth and great form. Even fitness professionals and super strong lifters commonly do it with "butt wink", i.e. when the tailbone tucks down at the bottom position. This means that the spine is bending and the pelvis might be in a less stable position, which causes excessive stress on the low back with heavy or frequent squatting. While it may not necessarily cause back pain or injury, I recommend erring on the side of caution--it may be just a matter of time or unfortunate circumstances.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
This video explains the first things I'll try to help someone correct butt wink. If those things and practice with a mirror don't work, I would then look at checking ankle and hip mobility, which can also limit butt wink-free squat depth.
‚Ä¢

caption:
Better ab exercises for back health!
¬†
üëâDesk workers definitely need to train their core, but often don't do it well even if they do feel the burn in the abs. Ab roll outs are great IF performed properly. No need to buy a special ab roll out device though! I actually prefer teach people to do this exercise with a stability ball. Otherwise, wheeled furniture can work too. 
üëâTips:
‚úîÔ∏è- From start to finish of every rep, keep your tail bone tucked down (belly button pointing to your nose) so your low back doesn't arch excessively.
‚úîÔ∏è- Keep your body in a straight line from head to knees. Do not bend at the hips when lowering. You will feel your glutes engage if you do this.
‚úîÔ∏è- Only go as low as you can while keeping your low back flat. Push your arms down and pull them towards you to get back to the start position (don't stick the butt up as you return).
‚úîÔ∏è- You should really feel the abs work without pressure in the low back.
‚Ä¢

caption:
Spend a lot of time sitting at your desk? Want a nicer butt?
¬†
üëâThere's a good chance you would benefit from stretching your hip flexors, which can get tight from all that sitting.
Tight hip flexors can contribute to
‚òπÔ∏èPoor posture
‚òπÔ∏èSleepy (and thus flatter) glutes
‚òπÔ∏èBack or knee pain
¬†
Key points for properly stretching your hip flexors:
‚úîÔ∏èTuck your tailbone so your belly button points to your nose. This involves engaging the abs and glutes on the back leg.
‚úîÔ∏èRaise the arm and twist and/or side bend towards the front leg as shown.
‚úîÔ∏èFeel the stretch in front of the hip of the back leg.
‚úîÔ∏èPerform the stretch for about 30 seconds dynamically (~4-5 reps), then hold the stretch statically for 30 seconds.

While it may not necessarily cause back pain or injury, I recommend erring on the side of caution--it may be just a matter of time or unfortunate circumstances.
¬†
üëâThis video explains the first things I'll try to help someone correct butt wink. If those things and practice with a mirror don't work, I would then look at checking ankle and hip mobility, which can also limit butt wink-free squat depth.
‚Ä¢

caption:
Walking is a great way to incorporate movement AND get out in nature. If you want to strengthen your muscles while walking, simply perform some walking lunges during the walk! Tips:
üëâKeep your front knee in line with an imaginary line running from the hip and ankle (front view).
üëâLean slightly forward at the torso to engage your glutes more.
üëâYou don't need to kill your legs to get the benefits: Start with even 5 per side, walk for a few minutes to recover, then repeat. Something is better than nothing!
üëâ Descend slowly but ascend into the next step quickly.

Use it or lose it! If you never have to reach or lift overhead, there's a good chance you will lose this ability. Overhead lifting can help you keep your shoulders healthy. Here's how to do an overhead press in a half kneeling position, which helps you minimize pressure on the low back:
1. Get into a half kneeling position as shown.
2. Hold the weight in the working arm (opposite to front leg) with the palm facing towards you.
3. Press the weight straight up. Rotate the arm so that the palm is facing away from you in the final position.
¬†
‚ùå Don't allow the ribs to flare out or back to arch to avoid putting pressure in the back.

caption:
Seated shoulder press with band.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you're looking to spend a little bit on exercise equipment, bands are probably the best option to start with: They're easy to travel with, inexpensive, and versatile. Additionally, they have one advantage you won't get with weights: the resistance level changes during the movement.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
This property, known as accommodating resistance, is useful in several exercises such as the shoulder press. When this movement is performed with regular weights, the effort normally diminishes as the hands approach the top of the movement due to the physics of gravity. When performed with bands, the band provides more resistance as it gets stretched such that the movement requires more uniform effort throughout the entire range. You can also make the resistance heavier or lighter by adjusting how you grip the band or by layering bands.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
Eccentric single leg glute bridge.
¬†
üçëThis exercise starts off similarly as the regular glute bridge, but on the way down, you're only using one leg. This makes the exercise not only heavier, but requires more hip and core stabilization.
¬†
1. Lie on your back with your feet together close to your butt.
2. Lift your hips up by peeling your body off the floor starting from the butt until the body forms a straight line from the knees to shoulders. The low back should remain flat (think about pointing the belly button to the nose).
 3. While keeping the hip bones level, bring one knee to your chest so you're only supported on one leg. Hold for the indicated time before lowering down on only the supporting leg.
¬†
When you lift one leg up, don't let the hip of the unsupported side drop down--this requires you to engage the core and glutes. The wider apart your feet are at the start, the harder it will be to keep the hips level, so start with the feet touching together.

caption:
Split squat jump
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
No time for gym and no weights at home? No problem. Once you've mastered the split squat, adding a jump will force your muscles to work harder so you move faster. It will also train good landing mechanics--if you can do it properly. Tips for good execution:
üëâThe feet should be about hip width apart from side to side.
üëâFrom the front view (i.e. if watching yourself in the mirror), the hip, knee, and ankle of the front leg should remain in one line, especially as you land.
üëâWhen descending, the front foot should remain flat on the floor while only the ball of the back foot in contact with the floor. Both feet should remain pointing forward.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
To advance:
üëâIncrease repetitions.
üëâAim higher.
Switch the leg positions mid air to land with the opposite leg forward.
üëâWant to give this a try but not sure if you're doing it correctly? Post a video and tag me, or send me the video in a DM.
‚Ä¢

Had a fun time facing of @takuma_oki in the snatch. I didn't win (congrats to him!), but got a small personal record. 

In the past, I would have been upset about not winning. I was once at a seminar where I was bothered because I couldn't deadlift as much as the other women (who where all bigger than me and actual competitive powerlifters). I then realized that this sort of comparison was a source of a lot of unnecessary unhappiness over something so trivial. 

There's a bright side and dark side to everything. This friendly competition gave me the motivation to snatch more consistently. Looking at what others can do can let you know what is possible, but use it to motivate you to take the right actions consistently rather than to simply feel inadequate.

caption:
Knee pain is super common. A couple years ago, both my knees were achy anytime I squatted or lunged with bodyweight. Oddly enough, with heavy weight, I did not feel knee pain. These days, my left knee still clicks uncomfortably with light squats/lunges, but when I use heavy weight OR concentrate on tensing up my muscles more, the clicking goes away. When I hit a personal record on the squat jerk last week, my left knee felt fine.

Knee pain can have many difference causes. If you feel clicking or grinding in the knees, it might be from muscle imbalances/tightness causing the knee cap to not glide properly as the knee bends/straightens. I suspect this is what's going on in my left knee right now. If your quadricep muscles are really tight, it could compress the knee cap as you bend the knees, as was happening to both my knees a couple years ago. If your knees are poorly aligned (valgus) during squatting, lunging, climbing, or running, that causes extra stress on the knees and can lead to pain also. All these causes of pain can be addressed using movement and lifestyle--don't just accept that you have "bad knees" if you haven't been properly assessed. Comment below if you have achy knees and could use some help!

caption:
Morning low intensity cardio on the indoor bike trainer.
In the first 3 minutes, I thought there was NO WAY the burning in my legs would allow me to continue for 30+ minutes at 60-70% maximum heart rate, but after 3 minutes, the burn subsided and my body was in cruise control.
Warming up is not simply for injury prevention. The processes in your body actually take time to ramp up to the level necessary for efficient exertion. This applies for both cardio activities and strength/power activities. A proper warm up at light intensity allows for the following minutes/sets to be better.
¬†
Thanks to Wilson for lending me his bike trainer. Now I have no excuse to do cardio!

caption:
The basic plank is a great exercise that is a much better option than crunches/sit ups because they train the core muscles in the same way they would be used in daily life--by keeping the torso stable against external forces.
¬†
Here's a plank variation to challenge your core (and shoulders!) even more: the plank with alternating leg lift.
üëâ Start with the elbows directly under the shoulders, forearms parallel to each other, chest pushed away from the floor (not sunken down).
üëâ Slowly peel yourself inch by inch off the floor¬†starting the upper abdomen down to the knees. As you do so, you will your abdominals activate starting from the top to the bottom.
üëâ Keep back flat by pointing the belly button to the nose. In the final position, the body should almost form a straight line from head to feet. You will feel your butt and abs work to hold the position. Don't let your lower back arch. 
üëâ Alternate between picking each foot off the floor while keeping the rest of the body still--don't let the hips/torso rotate. Perform 5 lifts per side. Rest and repeat for 3-6 sets.
¬†

caption:
Eccentric single leg glute bridge.
¬†
üçëThis exercise starts off similarly as the regular glute bridge, but on the way down, you're only using one leg. This makes the exercise not only heavier, but requires more hip and core stabilization.
¬†
1. Lie on your back with your feet together close to your butt.
2. Lift your hips up by peeling your body off the floor starting from the butt until the body forms a straight line from the knees to shoulders. The low back should remain flat (think about pointing the belly button to the nose).
 3. While keeping the hip bones level, bring one knee to your chest so you're only supported on one leg. Hold for the indicated time before lowering down on only the supporting leg.
¬†
When you lift one leg up, don't let the hip of the unsupported side drop down--this requires you to engage the core and glutes. The wider apart your feet are at the start, the harder it will be to keep the hips level, so start with the feet touching together.

caption:
Are your glutes SLEEPY? In the modern world, it's common for the glutes to be sleepy, which can cause back or knee issues. The glute bridge is a great exercise to correct this. Here's how to do it:
1. Lie on your back with your feet close to your butt at about hip width or wider. You can have your feet pointed slightly outwards.
2. Lift your hips up by peeling your body off the floor starting from the butt until the body forms a straight line from the knees to shoulders. The knees should move in line with the feet. The low back should remain flat (think about pointing the belly button to the nose).
 3. Hold for the indicated time before lowering down.
¬†
üëâ You should primarily feel the muscles in the butt working and no strain from the low back.
üëâ Experiment with different stance widths to find the width that allows for the most activation in the gluteal (butt) muscles.
üëâ If you feel pressure in the low back, maintain a flatter back throughout the movement.
üëâ If you feel more work from the back of the thighs than in the butt, imagine pushing your feet away from you body (without actually moving them) in the final position.

caption:
Use it or lose it! If you never have to reach or lift overhead, there's a good chance you will lose this ability. Overhead lifting can help you keep your shoulders healthy. Here's how to do an overhead press in a half kneeling position, which helps you minimize pressure on the low back:
1. Get into a half kneeling position as shown.
2. Hold the weight in the working arm (opposite to front leg) with the palm facing towards you.
3. Press the weight straight up. Rotate the arm so that the palm is facing away from you in the final position.
¬†
‚ùå Don't allow the ribs to flare out or back to arch to avoid putting pressure in the back.

caption:
Prone T back extension.
By changing the position of your arms, you can make the prone back extension more/less challenging for the low back muscles. The T position can also help you target the postural muscles of the shoulder.
üëâ Lie on your stomach with your arms out the sides and thumbs pointing up to the ceiling.
üëâ Lift your head and shoulders just slightly off the floor, keeping the head/neck aligned with the torso (face should you facing the floor). Then lift the arms off the floor.
üëâ To engage the core and low back muscles more, imagine lifting everything above the hips off the floor (even though the abdomen remains on the floor).
üëâ Don't arch your back excessively. To minimize pressure on the low back, you can perform this with a cushion or Bosu ball underneath your lower stomach. I advise against lifting the legs because this makes it harder to maintain a neutral spine.
üëâ Don't let the shoulders shrug towards your ears--the upper trapezius muscles are overactive in many people already, so no need to make that worse.

caption:
Before doing this sumo deadlift personal record today, I failed my first 2 attempts with 5 lbs less weight. Guess what I told myself to help me succeed the lift?
#squeezetheanus üòÅ
This cue is not to squeeze the glutes, but actually to activate the pelvic floor muscles, which works with the core to stabilize the spine so you can express your full strength. I know for me it makes a difference when lifting heavy.
@takuma_oki helped me film this, and he and I will be competing end of Aug to see who has the best conventional deadlift and sumo deadlift to body weight ratio. Who will win? Who else wants to join?

üí™ It's exciting to hit personal records. In 2017/18, I trained ~10 hours a week without making any progress on the main lifts I was training for, likely from under eating and over stressing. In the past 11 months, I added 40 lbs to my conventional deadlift (which I started training in 2014) despite only training 2-4 hours per week average thanks to focusing on recovering health (and squeezing the anus). This shows that athletic improvements also depend on lifestyle and health, not just training alone.

Side plank hip tap on knees.
The side plank is an exercise for the core AND the glutes (particularly the side glutes, or gluteus medius). The side plank hip tap is a variation that gets these glutes to work a little harder. If the full side plank is too challenging, perform side planks with the knees on the floor.
Tips:
üëâBend at the hips, not at the waist/spine.
üëâPush the hips forward at the top position to fully lock out (extend) the hips.
üëâHold the last rep for 10 seconds to further build endurance in the abs.
üëâYou should feel your abs and glutes working, but not pressure in the low back.

caption:
Mobility time! The "push up walk out" exercise is good for:
- Getting a stretch in the back of your legs (hamstrings).
- Activating the core.
- Activating muscles that stabilize the shoulders.
¬†
üëâ1. As you reach the hands to the floor, keep the knees as straight as you can to stretch the hamstrings.
üëâ2. The bottom position is a plank: Your body should form a straight line from the head to the feet. The neck should be aligned with the spine. The chest should be pushed away from the floor (this activates some shoulder stabilizing muscles).
üëâ3. As you return to the standing position, imagine pushing the floor away from you with your arms. Keep the knees as straight as you can.

You CAN change your skeleton!
During fast movements such as jumping, the body will tend to revert to patterns it is used to doing. For many people, the knees will tend to buckle towards each other, which is a sign that the body is not CONTROLLING the hip and ankle joints well--it's not simply the way you're built. This inward knee buckling leads to ACL injuries during fast changes in direction such as those seen in field sports, especially in women. When your glutes work better, not only will you be more bootylicious, but also keep your knees healthier and legs stronger. üçë Here are Lynda's jumps on the same day before and after an exercise she did to wake up the glutes and foot muscles. The one thing you must master before trying a fad diet.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In a society where it is so easy to consume calories, eating according to hunger and satiety (e.g. homeostatic eating) is a foundational nutrition skill that would not only reduce rates of overweight and obesity, but also eliminate many of the anxieties surrounding food and bodyweight. There‚Äôs no need to count calories or eat only salads to get and stay at a healthy bodyweight. Furthermore, when you get used to experiencing brief periods of hunger, you learn that it‚Äôs not an emergency and can act accordingly (no need to grab that snack bar if you can wait a bit for a nutritious meal instead).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Why am I so weak today?
Truth is, some days you'll feel strong, some days you'll feel weak. I could tell during my warm up that I was not as strong today but wanted to test out my 1 rep max anyway (as encouraged by @coach_jure) for the first time in years. After hitting a 1 rep max personal record, I failed all my subsequent attempts, even at the weight that I had done for 3 reps just 9 days prior. Perhaps I could have pushed harder but the failed attempt shook my confidence. Next time will be better.

So many things impact how strong you feel at a particular moment: environment, psychology, energy, stress, illness, sleep, nutrition, hormones (especially for women), etc. That's why it's important to look at the trend rather than get hung up on any one particular day.

Snacking is fine as long as it‚Äôs healthy, right?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In a fed state on a typical diet that includes carbohydrates, the body prioritizes burning carbohydrates over burning fat for energy. The body will shift towards using more fat for fuel when it is in a fasted state. If your body doesn‚Äôt spend much time in a fasted state because you‚Äôre eating/drinking carbs all day, it will be ‚Äúout of practice‚Äù with burning fat for fuel and thus be more reliant on carbohydrates for energy. If you‚Äôre not good at using fat for fuel, your brain and body will have a tough time if you haven‚Äôt eaten in a while, which means your energy, concentration, and mood will be worse. A healthy body should be able to use both carbohydrates and fat for fuel, as well as remain clear-headed during typical daily activities when fasted for several hours.

How to fast without starving. 
Fasting sits on a continuum. On one end is eating/drinking calories all day. On the opposite end is eating nothing for weeks. Neither of these extremes is desirable. 
Intermittent fasting is somewhere in the middle of the spectrum. It provides several health and body composition benefits and many people can adopt it fairly consistently long term, but it may not be doable for others. 
Also on the spectrum is simply waiting until you are hungry, or in a fasted state, before eating again. In a time where it‚Äôs so easy for us to access food quickly and eating is often done mindlessly while on Netflix or Instagram, the ability to eat according to hunger and fullness signals would not only reduce rates of overweight and obesity, but also eliminate many of the anxieties surrounding food and bodyweight. 
Here‚Äôs an approach everyone can use to get some of the benefits of intermittent fasting: Let your stomach growl before eating! This allows you to get some of the benefits from being in a fasted state for those health benefits.

Snack to support yourself!
While I talk about why we should get comfortable with NOT snacking, everything is context dependent. There are definitely times when it is a good idea to eat even if not hungry, such as:
‚Ä¢ If your schedule only allows you to eat a certain times.
‚Ä¢ If you need to eat proactively to support physical training and recovery. Some athletes expend so much energy with training/competition that the only way they can eat enough food to support it is to eat when not hungry.
‚Ä¢ If you need optimal mental performance (e.g. writing an exam, perform surgery).
‚Ä¢ If you know that waiting until hungry will cause you to binge later.
‚Ä¢ You have some sort of medical condition or are taking medication that requires eating at certain times.
‚Ä¢ Snacking is the only way to avoid undereating.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
Gimme a break‚Ä¶from snacking
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you tend to graze or drink caloric beverages throughout the day, or snack when not hungry, see how you feel with reducing the number of times you eat. This can look different depending on what you are currently doing: ‚Ä¢ If you drink creamy/sugary coffee/tea or pop between meals, cut them out or only have them with meals.
‚Ä¢ If you eat snacks at your desk while working, cut them out (even if they are healthy).
‚Ä¢ If you eat 5 times a day, try eating 4 times per day.
‚Ä¢ If you never experience a growling stomach between meals, wait until that happens before eating.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
There are no hard or fast rules about how to go about this experiment to get benefits. It can take time for you to adjust to eating less frequently. If your brain and body are used to running on carbohydrates most of the time, it will take time for you to become better at using fat for fuel. If you‚Äôre feeling really unwell (e.g. poor mood/energy, dizziness), take a more gradual approach and listen to your body. ‚Ä¢
