Squat myths busted!
‚ùå Myth: You must keep your feet hip width and pointing straight. ‚úîÔ∏è Truth: Pick a stance width that allows you to squat as deeply as possible with good form, ideally with your thighs parallel to the floor or lower in the bottom position. The feet can point straight ahead or slightly out to the side (up to 30 degrees). For most people, the ideal stance with is slightly wider than hip width with the feet pointing slightly to the side, but you will need to experiment to see what feels best. Whatever foot angle you choose, make sure the knees move in line with your feet to keep the knees healthy long term.
‚ùå Myth: Don't go past parallel. ‚úîÔ∏è Truth: Descend as deeply as you can while maintaining food form: Stiff spine, heels and toes in contact with the floor, chest facing forward. Squatting deeper generally allows for better leg strength and muscle development.
‚ùå Myth: Don't let your knees go past your toes. ‚úîÔ∏è Truth: If you're squatting deep enough, your knees will likely go slightly past your toes. Ensure that the heels stay on the floor. üëç Here's a great tip: Having a weight in front of the body helps you stay more balanced and thus squat deeper. The weight can be a dumbbell, barbell, or other weighted object. Have more questions or want some more guidance on your fitness? Comment below! This exercise helps to:
‚úîÔ∏è Increase active range of motion of the shoulders and thoracic spine.
‚úîÔ∏è Activate muscles involved in counteracting hunch back and rounded shoulder posture.

It's called the wall angel!¬†Execution:
üëâ1. Sit or stand with the back of the hip bones and shoulders touching the wall.
üëâ2. Bring the arms to the wall and slide them upwards, aiming to straighten the elbows and touch the hands together while keeping the entire arm (including the elbows) on the wall.
Most people will not be able to keep the back of the forearms against the wall the entire movement. Squeeze the shoulder blades together and aim to keep the arms as close to the wall as possible even if they come off the wall.
üëâ3. Keep the arms on the wall as you slide them back to the start position.
üëâKeep lower back neutral (avoid excessive arch) during the exercise. To avoid cheating by arching the lower back, perform exercise while seated with the hips against the wall.

.
Silvia is a kinesiologist, personal trainer, and nutrition coach. She became drawn to weight training for its health benefits, as well as its role in improving the body in a way that everyone can participate in.
.
Her friend showed her a YouTube video of an Olympic weightlifting athlete, which sparked her interest. From then, she decided to join an Olympic weightlifting club and got hooked! She was intrigued by the¬†technical skills required by the snatch and clean & jerk, as well as the sense of achievement from seeing herself improve with practice. The ups & downs she experienced as a competitive athlete gave her profound insight about human behaviour and ultimately allowed her to become a better coach.
.
Silvia has been coaching clients with exercise/movement since 2014, but she was never satisfied. Coaching made her realize the flaws with the physical education and healthcare systems in effectively helping people stay healthy and avoid pain/injury.
.
In 2018, she switched from being an Injury Rehabilitation Professional to a Personal Trainer. However, this career change didn‚Äôt provide her relief from her frustrations with the system. She quickly realized that people who needed professional guidance often couldn't put in the time/money.
.
Since then, Silvia‚Äôs mission has been to provide individualized and accessible professional exercise and nutrition guidance, so people can stay healthy and not feel defeated by their bodies. Ultimately, Silvia wants to change the government/institutional policies and practices to make professional, customized exercise guidance as accessible as seeing a doctor.

Squeeze the anus (this is a cue I use to engage the pelvic floor üòÇ). Create intra-abdominal pressure with 360 expansion. You are probably wasting time when you do planks.
Planks are actually a great ab exercise, but so many people do them inefficiently or just plan wrong! Holding for 10-sec at a time is all you need, and if you do it right, your abs will be burning. The keys are how you initiate the plank, the position of your low back, and your intention as you hold. Here's how (this video shows the plank on the knees):
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Start with the elbows directly under the shoulders, forearms parallel to each other, chest pushed away from the floor (not sunken down).
Slowly peel yourself inch by inch off the floor¬†starting the upper abdomen down to the knees. As you do so, you will your abdominals activate starting from the top to the bottom.
Keep back flat by pointing the belly button to the nose. In the final position, the body should almost form a straight line from head to feet. You will feel your butt and abs work to hold the position. Don't let your lower back arch. 
For more intensity, imagine pulling the elbows down to the knees (body stays still, but it increases abdominal activation).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
I just helped you save time with your ab training. You're welcome. Have more questions or want some more guidance on your fitness? Comment below! My goal is to help people fit exercise and healthy eating into their busy lives so they have the energy and confidence to kick butt in life.

Getting visible abs takes time. For women, it is particularly challenging and not always possible while staying healthy due to the hormonal changes that occur when getting lean. How long depends on your starting point. If you want abs, you‚Äôre going to need to lose fat, not simply do a lot of ab exercises. Here‚Äôs how to do that:
üëâLift heavy in the gym. Focus on big, compound lifts 80% of the time. This will help build or maintain muscle. It does not mean doing endless amount of ab exercises. In fact, spending a ton of time on just abs means you're missing the opportunity to do the exercises that will have a bigger impact on your physique and function (and train the core at the same time), such as squats, deadlifts, rows, pull ups, presses, etc.
üëâEat in a calorie deficit. This may mean you will feel a dull hunger or have cravings, or at least really change what you're eating.
üëâEat high protein. This will help you build or maintain muscle throughout the process.

Shoulder issues like tightness, pinching, and left-right asymmetry are common when the shoulders are rounded with all the sitting we do. Here's a stretch which may help: posterior shoulder capsule stretch.
1. Squeeze the shoulder blades together as you bring the hand to the opposite shoulder so that elbow is at shoulder height.
2. Use the opposite arm to pull the elbow across the body.
3. Keep the shoulder blades squeezed together throughout the stretch so that you feel the stretch on the back of the shoulder joint (where the arm connects to the body) instead of in between the shoulder blades. Hold for 30-60 seconds.

Being able to bend at the hip while keeping your spine rigid is important to keep your back healthy. Back pain is one of the leading causes of missed time from work. Practice the hip hinge pattern so you can use proper form when doing weighted versions of this movement.
How to do it:
1. Start standing nice and tall with good posture. Pretend the spine is stiff as a rod.
2. Fold your body at the hips by pushing your butt back and bringing your head down.
3. Bend down as low as you can without bending the spine. As you approach the bottom position, you will feel a stretch on the back of your thighs/knees and the knees will bend slightly. The shins should stay vertical (the knees should not be significantly forward relative to the ankles).
4. Imaging pushing the floor down with your legs as you stand up. You should primarily feel the muscles on the back of the thighs (hamstrings) and butt (glutes) working as you stand up.

Here is a way to train to lift heavy without actual weight--isometric deadlift with a towel. By the way, I'm looking for 3 time-crunched professionals who want to lose weight and feel energized even with a sedentary office job, starting on June 1st. It's a remote program, so you can join from anywhere in the world. If that's you, comment 'tell me more' below and I'll message you with the details.

üëâInstructions:
1. Stand in the middle of a bath towel folded 1 or 2 times lengthwise.
2. Grasp the towel on either side of the feet.
3. Get into the bottom position of the hip hinge and position the hands so there is no slack in the towel. The hands will be somewhere between knee and ankle height.
4. Try to stand up by pushing the floor down with your legs. Because you are continuing to grip the towel as you do this, your body will remain still despite exerting (this is an isometric hold). Exert for 5-10 seconds. Rest for the equivalent duration before doing the next repetition. Make sure to breath! Start with 5-10 reps .
To advance:
üëâPut in more effort! Isometric holds are a relatively safe way to push yourself. An exception is if you have high blood pressure, in which case more effort and longer holds will increase blood pressure further.
üëâExtend the duration of each repetition to up to 30 seconds.
üëâIncrease repetitions.
üëâDecrease rest time between reps.

No time for the gym? No problem.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
People love to train abs, but often don't do them well even if they do feel the burn in the abs. Ab roll outs are great IF performed properly. If you have a stability ball or barbell with bumpers, use those. Otherwise, wheeled furniture can work too. Tips:
- From start to finish of every rep, keep your tail bone tucked down (belly button pointing to your nose) so your low back doesn't arch excessively.
- Keep your body in a straight line from head to knees. Do not bend at the hips when lowering. You will feel your glutes engage if you do this.
- Only go as low as you can while keeping your low back flat. Push your arms down and pull them towards you to get back to the start position (don't stick the butt up as you return).
- You should really feel the abs work without pressure in the low back.

üëâWhen you first try this exercise, keep the toes tucked underneath your heels. Push through the toes to help you return back up. If you want to challenge yourself more, perform this with the toes pointed away from your shins.

Consistency leads to progress. As we get older, we need to work harder to maintain strength, muscle, and bone density. If you only have limited time for exercise, why not make sure it gives you the most total benefit? 
My routine is super boring, but I can measure the progress directly. Yesterday, I had a 3RM personal record on my front squat; the last time was in 2018 when I was more hardcore. For me, progress is more important than avoiding boredom. 
I don't train hard these days, but I have been training daily since the quarantine. I spend about 15-25 min on 1-2 exercises, and the weekly routine consists of only 5 exercises. Each day, I only aim to do one exercise--anything else is a bonus. It's not the optimal way to make progress, but it is still progress. 
Unstructured exercise is great too. I do those weekly on Zoom with my teams at Equinox and at Engineered Bodies, but I see those primarily as social opportunities with training being a bonus.

Identity. Who are you? Who do you want to be? 
Our identity shapes our behaviours, often very unconsciously. If want to create a habit, finding a way to align the action with your identity is a powerful way to make you follow through. I learned about the power of identity after my identity as a competitive weightlifter drove me to train 5-6 days a week consistently for the first time in my life from 2015-2018. I never enjoyed working out enough before that time. Unfortunately, I held on to this identity so strongly that it became more important than my health and work. This identity blinded me from logic, and no one was able to shake me from this irrationality. 
For those of you who are having a hard time doing something that you know is good for you or for someone you care for, how is that action aligned with your identity? Is there another identity that is blocking you?

Why you need to hold yourself back when you return to the gym
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
After taking weeks off of your usual exercise routine, you'll be tempted to go as hard your body can handle. No matter what you've done in the past, jumping back into heavy or repetitive exercises can be a recipe for injury. That's because the tendons and ligaments lose their "strength" faster than the muscles and need to play catch up with what the muscles can handle.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Here's how to transition back to the gym safely:
üí™Compare what you've been doing in the past few weeks with what your usual routine was before. Start with doing something that is reasonably in between the two in terms of intensity and volume. üí™Stay far away from failure for any given set, even if your muscles feel like they can handle more. You'll probably still be sore anyway after the time off. üí™Ramp up intensity and volume gradually over a few weeks. üí™Don't forget to support recovery with good sleep, nutrition, and stress management. üí™Avoid taking OTC anti-inflammatories medications if possible. The soreness you're feeling is actually super important for proper repair of the body, and NSAIDS can impair how tendons and ligaments heal.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
There's no need to rush. You're already going to progress more than you would be by doing more than before. An injury will only further set you back. (Shout out to @mihaelaaa.toma for capturing my last lifting session at the weightlifting club before everything got shut down due to Covid-19).

How you can do interval training without killing your joints or using equipment.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
High(er) intensity cardio training is superior in many ways to cardio done at a steady pace:
üëâSame or more fitness improvement in less time.
üëâHelps increase muscle mass and fat loss--just compare how a sprinter looks compared to a long distance runner.
üëâDoes not increase appetite and can actually suppress appetite, unlike endurance training. If your goal is fat loss, this is an important consideration!
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Despite this, I still don't recommend sprinting or running for most people because it's hard on the joints, especially since most people don't have good running (or even walking) form to begin with. One way to get the benefits of HIIT cardio is to run up flights of stairs. Running up stairs is actually less stressful on the joints than running on level ground (descending stairs is more stressful on joints, especially if your running technique sucks).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Here's a stair workout you can try:
üèÉRun up a flight of stairs, ideally a total distance of 1 or more floors but use what you have.
üèÉWalk back down.
üèÉIf needed, take a short rest before repeating.
The recovery time between reps and total workout time will depend on your fitness level and how intense it is. Even a 3 reps will be better than nothing, so just get started! The quicker you run up, the longer the recovery. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you'd like guidance on designing a custom HIIT program that is appropriate for your current fitness level and goals, comment below and I'll get in touch!

caption:
What's the best technique for lifting? üèãÔ∏èFor reaching/lifting below waist height, the movement chosen will be somewhere on the continuum of 2 extremes: (1)  A ‚Äúsquat‚Äù strategy (or lunge strategy), where the knees bend a lot. The muscles on the front of the thighs are the main muscles involved and there is more pressure on the knees compared to the hinge strategy. (2)  A ‚Äúhinge‚Äù strategy, where most of the bending happens at the knees. The muscles on the back of the thighs, glutes, and low back muscles are the main muscles involved, and there is more pressure on the low back and hips.

What strategy should you choose? That will depend on: ‚Ä¢ The shape of the object and other spatial constraints. For example, if you are lifting something in and out of a waist-height trash bin, squatting won‚Äôt work. ‚Ä¢ Your abilities, which will be based on your strengths and body proportions. ‚Ä¢ Whether or not you have any pain/injuries. A squat/lunge strategy might not feel good for someone with knee issues. A hinge strategy might not feel good for someone with low back or hip issues. 
When lifting everyday objects at home or at work, using a hybrid approach will be most suitable most of the time. This equally balances the pressure amongst the knees and back and will generally allow you to feel the strongest.

Simple Routine to Help You Kick Higher 
Kicking in kung fu, martial arts, dance, and soccer requires you to have flexibility in your legs and coordination so you can kick high and reduce injury risk. If have trouble with kicking due to tightness in your legs, here's a routine that will help. 
1. Leg lower #1: 
This helps you stretch the muscles on the back of your thigh of the top leg. Keep the knee of the top leg straight and toes pointed towards your shin. If you have trouble keeping the knee straight as you lower the other leg to the floor, hold the top leg closer to the floor. Eventually, work towards being able to perform this with the top leg vertical. Perform 2-3 sets of 10 reps. Do more as needed to improve flexibility.
2. Leg lower #2: 
This is almost like leg lower #1 except you need to hold the top leg in position without assistance. You‚Äôll feel your abs work! Take rests as needed. Perform 2-3 sets of 10 reps.
3. Controlled front kick:
This move requires you to actively extend the leg, which will stretch the muscles on the back of the thigh as well as active muscles on the front of the thigh. It also requires you to balance on one leg. Fully straighten the knee as you kick and avoid using momentum. Perform 2-3 sets of 10-15 reps. 
4. Romanian deadlift (stiff-legged deadlift):
You will make great progress simply by doing the 3 exercises above. I love this exercise because you are strengthening muscles as you stretch them, and lifting heavy weight will help you get stronger, build muscle, and strengthen your bones. When done correctly, the muscles on the back of the thighs and the butt will be doing most of the work, but you will also be strengthening your core and back. This exercise can be performed with dumbbells, a kettlebell, a barbell, or odd objects like a bag of rice. If you are not sure how to perform this correctly, get guidance from a qualified professional such as a personal trainer, kinesiologist, or physiotherapist. Perform 3-5 sets of 8-12 reps with good form.

caption:
Romanian (Stiff-legged) Deadlift 
I love this exercise because:
‚Ä¢ It stretches AND strengthens the hamstrings at the same time. Not only does this kill two birds with one stone, but it has a more permanent impact on flexibility compared to a static stretch.
‚Ä¢ It teaches you how to do a hip hinge pattern, which allows to you more safe movement options in everyday life. Unfortunately, a lot of people don't know how to bend while keeping their back safe.
‚Ä¢ It trains endurance of the low back, upper back, and core in addition to the glutes and hamstrings. 
Tips:
‚Ä¢ Pick a weight that you can perform safely for 8-20+ reps. Go lighter than you think you can handle, as you will be limited by the strength of your low back. Perform 2-4 sets.
‚Ä¢ You should feel the back of the thighs and glutes work, especially on the way up.
‚Ä¢ You may feel the low back if the weight is heavy enough, but you should notice it more when lowering down than when standing up. 
If you're still unsure if you're doing this movement correctly, it's always worthwhile to get guidance from a personal trainer, kinesiologist, physiotherapist, or other movement specialist to help you keep your body healthy long term.

Prone Y (more advanced than the prone T)

Shoulder issues are so common: Whether it's the inability to reach overhead, pinching or pain with certain arm movements, or "frozen shoulder" (which I saw in so many female care aides and housekeeping staff), weak shoulder muscles affect people of all ages and fitness levels.

The push up is a strength exercise that doesn't require equipment, but doing them without balancing them out with other exercises can make our shoulders and posture worse than they already are. Here's an exercise requiring no equipment that helps keep you improve posture and keep the shoulders pain-free.

1. Lie on your stomach with your head resting on the floor and arms reached forward in a Y shape (about 45 deg angle from the head).
2. Reach arms forward as high as you can, shrugging the shoulders.
3. Pull your shoulders away from the floor and away from your ears.
4. While keeping your shoulder blades in that position, lift your arms off the floor and hold. It is more important to keep the upper arms reached forward than to lift the arms high.
5. Hold for 10 seconds for 6-10 reps. Feel the muscles in between and on the surface of the shoulder blade activate. For more challenge, perform while holding 1-3lb weights.

caption:
‚ö°One of the things we‚Äôve definitely learned during the past couple of months is the importance of having some extra food staples in our pantries ‚Ä¶ just in case!ü•´ üò±That can be a real struggle if you have a small kitchen or not much storage. üëâKeeping a supply of canned beans, lentils, quinoa, rice, gluten-free pasta, sauces, protein powder, nut butters, tuna, canned tomatoes, low-sodium soups, and other healthy pantry must-haves can take up a surprising amount of space. üç∑Plus, when your pantry is disorganized, it‚Äôs super easy to forget exactly what you have on-hand, which can cause waste and/or extra trips to the grocery store. üí°Here are some tips to make the most of what you have ‚Ä¶ and stay organized in the process! ‚óè ¬†Add wire baskets that hook underneath your cabinet shelving. Under shelf baskets are inexpensive and can almost double the amount of cabinet storage space.
‚óè ¬†Pick up a wire rack with hooks at the top to go over doors. These come in different sizes and can store spices, cleaning items, etc.
‚óè ¬†Add bars at the rear of your cabinets, and use S hooks to hang up your coffee cups, clearing out needed space. Or hang S hooks on your backsplash to store kitchen utensils, freeing up drawer space.
‚óè ¬†Use a plate rack to organize the covers for all your plastic reusable containers.
‚óè ¬†In really tight areas, turn a clear ‚Äúover the door‚Äù shoe organizer into a holder for snacks or cooking utensils. (This is also great for bathroom storage) ‚≠êThese are just a few ideas to get you started! Do you have any tips? Share them below! ‚§µ‚§µ

Crab bridge
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Train the glutes and upper body at the same time with this variation of the glute bridge. Whether you do this version or a different one, here's something to keep in mind:
üçëExperiment with different feet widths to see which one allows you to feel your glutes the most. For most people, this means the feet will be wider than hip width with the toes slightly pointing to the sides.
üçëFully lock out the hips! The torso and thigh should form a straight line. If you're having trouble with this, it could mean you need to work on either hip or shoulder mobility.
üçëLook forward (this activates your neck and abs).
üçëYou should not feel the back during this exercise. If this happens, work on keeping your tailbone tucked down (or think about pointing your belt buckle to your nose).

caption:
Shoulder issues are so common: Whether it's the inability to reach overhead, pinching or pain with certain arm movements, or "frozen shoulder" (which I saw in so many female care aides and housekeeping staff), weak shoulder muscles affect people of all ages and fitness levels.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
The push up is a strength exercise that doesn't require equipment, but doing them without balancing them out with other exercises can make our shoulders and posture worse than they already are. Here's an exercise requiring no equipment that helps keep you improve posture and keep the shoulders pain-free.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Prone "T" exercise: ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢1. Lie on your stomach with your head resting on the floor and arms out to the side in a "T" shape". 2. Pull your shoulders away from the floor and away from your ears (at the end of the video, I show what this looks like when performed upright).
3. While keeping your shoulder blades in that position, lift your arms off the floor and hold. Keep the arms in line with the shoulder (don't let them drift towards the body) and shoulders away from the ears (not shrugged).
4. Hold for 10 seconds for 6-10 reps. Feel the muscles in between and on the surface of the shoulder blade activate. For more challenge, perform while holding 1-3lb weights.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Let‚Äôs talk about progress in the gym because it ain‚Äôt always linear.
Sure, you can increase the amount of weight that you lift. But you can also lift the same weight more times. Both are great.
But there‚Äôs so much more to it. Being able to train with less rest, improvements in your mental game, bettering your range of motion, or lifting with a more difficult tempo are all ways to vary and improve.

When I posted this video originally, it was to show people that even without being in a gym, there are ways to train strength. In response, one of my male friends messaged me saying that my arms were bigger than his and that I was too "bulky" (since then, he has apologized). My body has changed a lot in the past few years: gained muscle, lost fat (with disordered eating), gained fat. Negative body image is a very subjective thing, and even when I was 20 lbs lighter at the peak of my weightlifting obsession, I felt like I was not as lean as I should be. *
*
It's one thing to feel insecure about yourself, but when that insecurity results in giving negative feedback about someone else's body, really consider the consequences and remember that you don't actually know what that person has gone through. Everyone has their own struggles which you can't see. I was reminded of this recently when I learned that friends have gone serious mental illness. *
*
Through help from counselling, I've been able to somewhat quiet down the negative self talk related to my body (please don't send any reassurance or bad mouth this male friend; that is not what this is about). I recommend others do the same if they struggle with self-esteem issues.
@bia_skincare

üí•If you use a lot of disinfecting cleaners in your house, YOU NEED TO READ THIS... üîé A study from Canada found disinfectants can affect gut bacteria in young children AND could lead to obesity. üëâDisinfectants are designed to kill bacteria and they are found in many home cleaning products. üë∂The researchers analyzed the gut microbiomes of more than 750 babies aged 3-4 months. Then, when the babies were ages 1 and 3, they recorded their weight. ‚ö°Scientists also looked at the child‚Äôs exposure to disinfectants, detergents, and eco-friendly cleaning products. üßêThey found that the babies in homes with regular disinfectant use had lower levels of some bacteria (haemophilus and clostridium) and higher levels of others (lachnospiraceae). Plus, their body mass index was higher when it was measured at age 3.

Researchers didn‚Äôt find these same results with babies exposed to eco-friendly cleaners. 
This isn‚Äôt to scare you- I just want you to be informed of the latest research! ‚ö°Our gut is affected not just by what we eat, but also our environment! üî•If this is a concern for you, it‚Äôs definitely worth looking into eco-friendly cleaners ... there are so many good ones on the market now. üëçDo you use eco-friendly cleaners? What‚Äôs your go-to?

You are probably wasting time when you do planks.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Planks are actually a great ab exercise, but so many people do them inefficiently or just plain wrong! Holding for 10-sec at a time is all you need, and if you do it right, your abs will be burning. The keys are how you initiate the plank, the position of your low back, and your intention as you hold.¬†Here's how:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Start with the elbows directly under the shoulders, forearms parallel to each other, chest pushed away from the floor (not sunken down).
Slowly peel yourself inch by inch off the floor¬†starting the upper abdomen down to the knees. As you do so, you will your abdominals activate starting from the top to the bottom.
Keep back flat by pointing the belly button to the nose. In the final position, the body should almost form a straight line from head to feet. You will feel your butt and abs work to hold the position. Don't let your lower back arch.
For more intensity, imagine pulling the elbows down to the knees (body stays still, but it increases abdominal activation).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Screw press
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢¬†
The screw press is similar to the windmill exercise but in a more stable position. It's great for shoulder, spine, and hip mobility; inner thigh & glute flexibility; core stability, and shoulder stability. It is a component of the Turkish Getup, but you can challenge your mobility a bit more by placing your forearm on the floor (to make it easier, reduce the range of movement by stopping once the palm touches the floor). Thanks, @ironkimono for this one!

Standing Y for lower traps
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
This is an exercise to help keep your shoulders healthy--super important in this modern world. Surprisingly, I've had 20-something female clients who had poor overhead mobility, and this exercise helped them after just a few sessions.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
1. Place arms on the wall to make a Y shape with the body. Reach arms up as high as you can, shrugging the shoulders.
2. Depress the shoulders, i.e. pull shoulder blades together and down towards the floor.
3. Rotate the arms so the thumbs point behind you (i.e. externally rotate the shoulders).
4. Move the shoulder blades down away from the ears and towards each other to lift arms away from the wall and hold, keeping the elbows straight and arms overhead. Feel the muscles between the shoulder blades working.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Being able to lift heavy weight is not enough. Everyone should do some sort of a single leg exercise to keep the body healthy. Single leg exercises train the glutes to stabilize the all the joints in the leg, which not only helps you get a round butt, but keep your back and knees healthy!
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢ 
The single leg deadlift, when done properly, is a great exercise that teaches good body mechanics and trains the butt AND the low back. This is important if you're a health care worker handling patients as it reduces your risk of low back injuries, which were common amongst the health care workers I've helped.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢ 
Correct form involves:
- Keeping the spine neutral.
- Keeping the pelvis level (one side should not be higher than the other).
- Feeling the glutes and back of the legs doing most of the work.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Craving sweets a lot? Here are some ways to minimize your sugar cravings:
(1) Make sure your meal/snack includes plenty of the following nutrients that help slow down digestion and absorption: protein, fibre, and a bit of healthy fat.
(2) Pick foods that are as minimally processed as possible. The more processed it is, the easier it is to eat and digest and the faster it could increase your blood sugar.
(3) Stay hydrated! Sometimes thirst is disguised as cravings for something sweet, possibly because¬†historically, we got water from fruit.
(4) Get enough sleep.
‚Ä¢

caption:
What does it mean to "lift with your legs, not your back?"
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
A couple things to consider when it comes to safe lifting:
(1) What is actually happening in the spine?
(2) How strong is your back?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Like many people, my dad used a squat strategy (knee-dominant, or "legs") to lift. He did not understand how to safely bend at the hips without bending the back. The ability to perform a good "hip hinge" pattern allows your body to have a wider variety of safe movement options, and also teaches safe spine position for all other movements. While the back muscles are always involved in lifting (or simply even standing upright), proper hip hinging actually primarily uses the back of the legs and the butt to generate most of the strength.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
It took a good amount of practice for him to hip hinge properly, but once he got it, I had him practice the movement with weight (@X3_bar) to really ensure he felt the legs doing more work than the back.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
So how do you make sure you lift safely?
(1) Aim to lift with a neutral spine no matter which lifting strategy you use.
(2) Become stronger than what you need to do! (3) Ideally, learn to use a knee-dominant, hip-dominant strategy, or something in between so you have more options.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
It's always worthwhile to get guidance from a personal trainer, kinesiologist, physiotherapist, or other movement specialist to help you keep your body long term, especially if you already have pain. Put your cravings on a time-out.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
One specific tactical strategy for overcoming cravings is to simply wait and sit with the discomfort of not satisfying the craving right away. Set a timer for 20 minutes. If after 20 minutes, you really still feel the need to indulge the craving, then maybe that is what you need in the moment. Waiting allows you to make a deliberate decision that you‚Äôre less likely to regret later. There‚Äôs nothing wrong with indulging occasionally if done mindfully. Often what will happen is that the craving will subside
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

What triggers you to fall into the habit of eating when not hungry? Today I had to resist my habit of snacking on almonds. 
One way I manage my food environment is by keeping almonds in the garage fridge because otherwise I can easily eat the whole bag--so addictive! I'm in the garage on most days lately because that is where my gym is set up, and today I had to resist the urge of falling into my habit of eating 10-15 almonds while doing some front squats.

Note: There's nothing wrong with eating a few almonds daily, but I need to practice what I preach once in a while, so am participating the 7-day no-snacking challenge I've created. 
#kitchendistancing #vancouver #yvr #fitness¬†#nutrition #nutritioncoach #personaltrainer

The One Type of Snack You Must Have as Much as Possible.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Is it almonds? Nope.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
It's movement--movement "snacks"! No matter how long or intense your workouts, being in one position for most of the day can make your body feel cranky and be bad for your health.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Also, did¬†you know that small bouts of movement/exercise are just as beneficial for health (and often even performance) as the equivalent exercise done all at once?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
These days, the idea of doing a long workout is not appealing, so instead, I aim to do a short session daily, which consists of 3-5 heavy sets of a heavy lower body exercise and push ups (I've been working toward a push up personal record).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
How are you adding movement snacks to your day?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In case you're wondering about the photo: I keep almonds in the garage (otherwise I risk finishing the bag), along with the unused elliptical machine and case of toilet paper. I know and my squat form is not perfect in this, but sometimes you lift for the soul.

Here's another no-equipment exercise that is helps to improve muscles involved in posture: The bent-over face pull to overhead reach.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Bend at the hips until the torso is about horizontal (keep back straight throughout).
Pull shoulder blades together as you bring your elbows up to shoulder height. 
Rotate the shoulders and reach the arms forward, keeping the arms as far from the floor as possible throughout. 
Reverse the steps and repeat.
Third view is given to more clearly demonstrate how the arms move relative to the body. Notice that the shoulder blades move in addition to the arms.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

What about the keto diet or intermittent fasting?
*
*
The keto diet has some benefits, though it also has many downsides. If you haven‚Äôt mastered the ability to eat according to hunger levels, you will likely eventually struggle with the same eating issues that you had before.
*
*
Intermittent fasting and time-restricted feeding can be a strategy that many people can adopt fairly consistently long term, but others may struggle with. *
*
Here‚Äôs an approach everyone can use to get some of the benefits of both the keto diet and intermittent fasting: Let your stomach growl before eating! This ensures you get into a fasted state in between meals. *
*

Covid-19 kitchen distancing: Why snacking all day (even on healthy foods) is sabotaging your body and mind
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
To me, the main benefit of not snacking/eating until hungry is psychological. In a society where it is so easy to consume calories, eating according to hunger and satiety (e.g. homeostatic eating) is a foundational nutrition skill that would not only reduce rates of overweight and obesity, but also eliminate many of the anxieties surrounding food and bodyweight. There‚Äôs no need to count calories to get and stay at a healthy bodyweight. Furthermore, when you get used to experiencing brief periods of hunger, you learn that it‚Äôs not an emergency and can act accordingly (no need to grab that Snickers bar if you can wait a bit for a nutritious meal instead).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Standing Y for lower traps
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
This is an exercise to help keep your shoulders healthy--super important in this modern world. Surprisingly, I've had 20-something female clients who had poor overhead mobility, and this exercise helped them after just a few sessions.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
1. Place arms on the wall to make a Y shape with the body. Reach arms up as high as you can, shrugging the shoulders.
2. Depress the shoulders, i.e. pull shoulder blades together and down towards the floor.
3. Rotate the arms so the thumbs point behind you (i.e. externally rotate the shoulders).
4. Move the shoulder blades down away from the ears and towards each other to lift arms away from the wall and hold, keeping the elbows straight and arms overhead. Feel the muscles between the shoulder blades working.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
TRY A NO-SNACKING EXPERIMENT. Here‚Äôs what it might look like:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢ If you tend to graze or drink caloric beverages throughout the day, or snack when not hungry, see how you feel with reducing the number of times you eat. This can look different depending on what you are currently doing: ‚Ä¢ If you drink creamy/sugary coffee/tea or pop between meals, cut them out or only have them with meals.
‚Ä¢ If you eat snacks at your desk while working, cut them out (even if they are healthy).
‚Ä¢ If you eat 5 times a day, try eating 4 times per day.
‚Ä¢ If you never experience a growling stomach between meals, wait until that happens before eating.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
There are no hard or fast rules about how to go about this experiment to get benefits. It can take time for you to adjust to eating less frequently. If your brain and body are used to running on carbohydrates most of the time, it will take time for you to become better at using fat for fuel. If you‚Äôre feeling really unwell (e.g. poor mood/energy, dizziness), take a more gradual approach and listen to your body. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
No gym? No problem.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Whether you're used to lifting heavy or not, there's a great chance you're missing movements where you move the body side to side. Your body needs to be able to move in all directions because life is unpredictable! Here are a few variations starting with the simplest:
‚Ä¢
(1) Lateral squat. ‚Ä¢
(2) Lateral lunge. ‚Ä¢
(3) Lateral lunge to high knee.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Benefits:
‚Ä¢
(1) Train stability and mobility of the hip, ankle, and foot to keep your back and knees healthy.
‚Ä¢
(2) Improve flexibility of your inner thigh and calf without doing yoga.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
 Things to keep in mind:
‚Ä¢
(1) The bending knee should always point in the same direction as the toes.
‚Ä¢
(2) Minimize twisting the torso or leaning it left/right, especially if using heavy weight.
‚Ä¢
(3) For the lateral lunges, point the toe as  you push off the foot.
‚Ä¢
(4) Just like for regular squats, push the butt back and lean the torso forward.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

Finally get a full push up, step 1/5: QUADRUPED PUSH UP
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
I‚Äôm counting down push up variations from hardest to easiest, so if the last one was too challenging, try this one. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢ 
I first created this push up variation for my mom as she had trouble maintaining a rigid torso during knee push ups. This version really focuses on training the upper body with less involvement of the core. (1) Get on your hands and knees. (2) Bend your elbows to lower your torso/head down and FORWARD until the forehead touches the floor, keeping the upper arms close to the body so that they are at 5 o'clock and 7 o'clock. (3) Push yourself back up to the start position OR into child pose. Pushing back into child pose would be easier because it requires less core strength and allows you to use your lower body muscles to pull the butt to the heels. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

caption:
Finally get a full push up, step 2/5: ECCENTRIC PUSH UP ON KNEES TO CHILD POSE
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
I‚Äôm counting down push up variations from hardest to easiest, so if the last one was too challenging, try this one. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢ 
I don‚Äôt know if anyone else uses this push up variation as I invented it for clients who had a tough time with the more common modified push up variations (e.g. back would sag on the way up). 1. Get into a plank position with knees of the floor: Tail bone tucked down so the low back is flat, chest pushed away from the floor so shoulders are in a good position, and neck aligned with your torso. The body should be in a straight line from the knees to the head.
2. Lower down slowly to the floor, keeping your arms at 5 o'clock and 7 o'clock.
3. Push yourself into child pose. If needed, help out the upper body by using your lower body muscles to pull the butt to the heels.
4. Reset and repeat.

A harder version of this one would be to keep the knees off the floor on way down (second video).

Greek usually has the most. Protein not only helps your body repair, rebuild, and recover, but it also keeps you feeling full between meals.
üòãTaste: Find one with a taste you enjoy, because it won‚Äôt do you any good if it just sits in your fridge!

This is the same as the full push up, except your hands are elevated on a higher surface such as a table, countertop, bench, or barbell on a rack. The lower the surface, the harder it is (I have some clients doing it with the hands on a 6‚Äù plyo box). Unlike wall push ups where you can only lower until the head touches the wall, this variation allows for full range of motion of the upper body, which ultimately is important for developing strength and muscle size. 
1. Get into an elevated plank position: Tail bone tucked down so the low back is flat, chest pushed away from the floor so shoulders are in a good position, and neck aligned with your torso. The body should be in a straight line from the feet to the head.
2. Lower down slowly until the surface touches the bottom of the chest (bottom of the bra).
3. Push up while keeping the torso rigid in a straight line; do not arch the back). ‚Ä¢

My fellow personal trainers at @equinox have a fitness challenge each month, and this month‚Äôs challenge is getting the most push ups in a row. My previous push up personal record back in September was 21, but recently, even doing 10 push ups was tiring and I couldn‚Äôt wrap my head around exceeding that previous record. ‚Ä¢

Applying my knowledge about exercise science and psychology, I decided that to just aim to do one set of push ups almost daily and simply add one rep each day. Within each day, I break down this action into even smaller steps by simply breaking down the set into mini sets within the set: Today I did 19 push ups and in my mind I was doing 3x5+4 reps. Finally get a full push up, step 5/5: Eccentric Push Up ¬üI‚Äôm counting down push up variations from hardest to easiest, so if this one is too challenging, keep your eye out for the next few posts! ¬ü
How long have you been doing push ups on the knees without being able to do a single full push up? I am passionate about getting women to strength train, and a full push up is very challenging exercise for many women. Following a well-designed progressive exercise program will be what ultimately gets you to that full push up. Simply doing knee push ups may never get you there. ¬ü
¬ü
The eccentric push up is the same as the full push up on the way down, but you have your knees on the floor when you push back up. The key points here: (1) The slower you lower down, the harder it will be and thus the better your training effect. (2) Maintain good alignment! Your body should be in a straight line from the head to the feet/knees; don‚Äôt let the low back droop down. (3) Keep your upper arms close to the body, approximately at 5 o'clock and 7 o'clock. ¬ü

‚≠êSuper cool NEW research shows just how important the bacteria in your gut is for your health ... ‚Ä¶ and also for preventing and treating disease in the future! üíØ

It‚Äôs not just the bacteria that matters, but also the genes they contain. ü§ìInteresting fact: your gut microbiome has 200 times more genes than your entire body! üí™We all know broccoli, cabbage and cauliflower are good for you, right? They contain vitamins, minerals, and fiber. üëâ But they also contain chemicals called glucosinolates. ü¶†There‚Äôs actually a bacteria in your gut ‚Äì called Bacteroides thetaiotaomicron ‚Äì that can transform those chemicals into compounds called isothiocyanates, which have protective effects against certain cancers. ü•¶ Amazing, right? Well, scientists have pinpointed exactly WHICH gene inside that bacteria that‚Äôs responsible for producing isothiocyanates ‚Äì and discovered that adding it to other bacteria helps them produce it, too! ü§ØMIND BLOWN! ü•óThe takeaway: Say yes to broccoli! And be sure to take care of your gut health with a healthy diet, enough sleep & exercise, and cutting back on stress ‚Ä¶ since they ALL affect your microbiome.

REFERENCE:
www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00493-8

Here are some possible signs that you are not eating enough carbs for your current situation:*
*
1.	Feeling cold.
2.	Feeling more tired than usual.
3.	Hair loss.
4.	Body aches, pain, or injuries (both minor and serious).
5.	Less frequent or absent menstruation in women (definitely a serious sign!).
6.	Difficulty falling or staying asleep.
7.	Poor mood (anxiety, depression, low self-esteem)
8.	Higher cravings for sweets or starches.
9.	Disproportionately high body fat in the midsection.
10.	Lower heart rate and blood pressure than expected.
11.	Digestive problems (usually bloating and/or constipation).
12.	Feeling dizzy more easily (orthostatic hypotension).
*
*
Of course, the symptoms above can have many different causes other than not eating enough carbs. This article is not a comprehensive medical guide, so do talk to a qualified doctor or dietician for personalized care if you are experiencing health problems.
*
*

The push up is a great exercise that not only trains the upper body, but also the core as well as even the lower body. 
It's unbelievable how few people actually do push ups with good form, including people who are otherwise very strong. The most common significant form issues are:
(1) arched lower back (lack of abdominal engagement), (2) not descending low enough (missed opportunity to strengthen the entire range of motion), and (3) elbows flared far from the body (missed opportunity to strengthen the triceps). In my demo of the full push up, notice:
(1) The body is in a straight line from the feet to the head. The low back is flat. In this video, I am looking up (so I go all the way down without kissing the floor), but facing the floor the entire time is even better for strengthening the neck. What we don‚Äôt want is for the head to be lower than the torso.
(2) I descend until my chest is almost touching the floor. (3) My arms are roughly 30 degrees from the body, or at about 5 o‚Äôclock and 7 o‚Äôclock. If I wanted to get the triceps to work more than my chest, I could keep the upper arms as close to the body as possible.
¬ü
¬ü

caption:
Of all the macronutrients that we eat, the body can make energy the most rapidly from carbohydrates. Not having enough carbohydrates in the body can impair your athletic performance and your ability to get good workouts. Beyond that, going low carb for a long time can have other undesirable effects.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Short term:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢	It can impair your body‚Äôs ability to make melatonin, which is important for falling asleep and staying asleep.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢	If your body‚Äôs blood sugar gets too low while you‚Äôre sleeping, you may wake up prematurely due a rise in stress-related hormones (including cortisol).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Long term:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢	The disrupted sleep has a host of other negative effects, including mood issues, lethargy, poor blood sugar regulation, cognitive impairment, and increased cravings.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢	Cortisol levels become disrupted. Cortisol is an important hormone for survival and for feeling energized, but when it is chronically higher than it should be (such as what happens when under any physical or mental stress), it has a lot of negative effects on your health and makes it harder to gain muscle and easier to store belly fat.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢	The chronic state of stress from being too low carb (even if you don‚Äôt perceive it) can decrease sex hormones (e.g. estrogen, testosterone), which has many other serious downsides. Women are more likely to experience this. Other factors that increase risk for disrupted sex hormones from not having enough carbs include high stress levels, high exercise intensity/duration, low body fat, and lower nutrient intake.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢In my next post, I will list some signs you might be eating too low carb. Have more questions or want some more guidance on your own meals and snacks? Comment below! My goal is to help food lovers eat healthier without hating life.
#vancouver #yvr #fitness  #nutrition #nutritioncoach #personaltrainer #carbs

No gym? No problem! Incorporate SPEED!
Adding weight is not the only way to make an exercise more challenging. The muscles activate more forcefully also when moving FASTER! 
The ability to move quickly is also important in many athletic pursuits and also can keep you safer (e.g. reacting quickly can help prevent a bad fall).
This is a reverse lunge to single leg hop. Things to keep in mind:
	1. Keep the hip, knee, and ankle in alignment when viewed from the front. This applies to both the bottom position as well as when landing.
	2. Point the toes down when you jump to get more power!
	3. Intentionally move the arms explosively in addition to jumping with the legs. Everything in the body is connected, and shoulder power contributes to hip power!
	4. Land softly to minimize joint stress.

caption:
Technically, the calories you get from vegetables and fruits are mostly from carbohydrates. Something like spinach can be LOW carb but still MOSTLY carb. Vegetables and fruit are a great way to get lots of micronutrients (vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, and other beneficial stuff) as well as fibre, so should generally be included in everyone‚Äôs diet. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

A common misconception people have is that complex carbs are healthy, and I think that‚Äôs partly because they assume complex carbs means fibre (not technically true). While healthier sources of carbs will tend to have complex carbs, many less nutritious foods like white bread, Cheetos, and tapioca pearls are technically mostly complex carbohydrates (starch) as well. What‚Äôs more important‚Äîand likely what most people think of when it comes to selecting better carbohydrates‚Äîis to look at the source:‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

How much micronutrients and fibre does it have?‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

How processed is it?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Will this make me feel good after, or will it make me feel tired/bloated/anxious/overeat or give me joint pain/acne/brain fog? ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Precision Nutrition‚Äôs healthy eating guidelines uses the term ‚Äúsmart carbs‚Äù, which can include fruit, starchy vegetables, tubers, whole grains, and other minimally processed carbohydrate sources. I love this term because:
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
1. It automatically rules out most high sugar foods and selects for higher fibre options.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
2. It does NOT mean you need to include grains in your diet! You can get plenty of carbohydrates from other whole food sources.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In my next post, I will list some of the health consequences of eating too low carb.

caption:
Here are ways to keep your blood sugar levels more stable and keep you fuller:‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

1)	Make sure your meal/snack includes plenty of the following nutrients that help slow down digestion and absorption (and thus slow down the rise in blood sugar after eating):‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
a)	Protein. A major bonus of protein is that it is particularly good for keeping you satiated so you‚Äôll have less hunger and cravings.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
b)	Fibre (e.g. in vegetables and whole grains).‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
c)	Fat (1-2 thumbs per meal is enough).‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
2)	Pick foods that are as minimally processed as possible. The more processed it is, the easier it is to eat and digest and the faster it could increase your blood sugar. For example, choose:‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
a)	Whole fruits instead of smoothies or purees.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
b)	Brown rice or oats instead of white rice or bread (even whole grain bread is relatively processed).‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
c)	Whole nuts instead of nut butter.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
3)	Eat until just satisfied. Even if you eat a nutritious meal with all the above components, the more you eat, the more your blood sugar level increases.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
4)	Eat slowly. This will help by ensuring you are less likely to overeat and by making the rise in blood sugar more gradual.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
5)	If you‚Äôre working overnight, try to get your main meal near the start of your shift. Your body‚Äôs ability to digest food and keep blood sugar stable is poorer during the time when it wants to be sleeping.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In my next post, I will discuss whether you even need to eat carbs.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

This is a simple sequence of events explaining how food affects blood sugar:
‚Ä¢ Food/drink is ingested. >> Food is broken down into smaller molecules (digestion). All carbohydrates are broken down into the smallest sugar molecules (except for fibre). >> Molecules of food, including sugar, are absorbed from the gut into our bloodstream. >> Blood sugar level rises. >> Blood circulation delivers the nutrients to cells all over the body. >> Cells absorb the sugar and other nutrients from the blood so they can make energy and function. >> Blood sugar level goes down. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Your blood sugar level is dynamic, and for optimal health and energy, it should remain within a tight range. During a fasted state (e.g. first thing in the morning), you will still have some sugar in your blood at a level that is more or less steady as you rest or go about light activity. The quicker and higher the blood sugar level rises after eating/drinking, the quicker and lower it will drop later on (due to the hormone insulin). Sometimes, the blood sugar can drop even lower than when you‚Äôre in a fasted state‚Äîknown as a ‚Äúsugar crash‚Äù or ‚Äúfood coma‚Äù. This state of having low blood sugar is not desirable. Not only will you feel sluggish and/or grouchy, but also more likely to crave sugary or starchy foods to restore your blood sugar level. Unfortunately, most people will crave something like chips or cookies rather than carrots.‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Many things affect how quickly and how much the blood sugar will rise after eating/drinking, including: ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢What and how much you ate, and even how you ate. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Your state of health (e.g. how much muscle you have, if you‚Äôre diabetic or prediabetic). ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Sleep quantity and quality. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Exercise and movement. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢Stress levels. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In my next post, I will focus on how food affects the dynamics of blood sugar levels‚Äîwe all gotta eat, no matter how busy we are! Have more questions or want some more guidance on your own meals and snacks? Comment below! My goal is to help food lovers eat healthier without hating life.

caption:
In the end, the thing that determines your body weight is energy balance: ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Energy balance = ‚Ä¢ the calories your body gets through food (energy in) ‚Ä¢ MINUS ‚Ä¢ the energy your body uses (energy out) ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
The laws of physics dictate that this will always hold true. However, in practice, so many things (physical and psychological) affect either of the two parts of the energy balance equation. For example: ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Some foods may trigger you to eat more calories than you need because they don‚Äôt help you feel full and/or are ‚Äúaddictive‚Äù. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Some foods may make you feel sluggish so you don‚Äôt want to move much, while other foods help you feel energized and ready to crush a work out. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you‚Äôve been dieting, your body will slow down its energy use to avoid starvation. A side effect of this is that you‚Äôll move around less and feel more tired. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
If you‚Äôre about to do a boxing match and need to get as many calories as you can right away, eating oatmeal with banana is going to be a lot harder than the equivalent calories of a sugary sports drink. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Various factors affect how many calories you actually absorb from food, such as the type of food, how processed the food is, how quickly the food passes through your gut, and even your gut bacteria. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
In summary, you can eat a ton of carbs and maintain or even lose body fat (and many people do) as long as you eat fewer calories than what your body uses. However, unless you‚Äôre a robot, the type of foods you eat and your lifestyle will make it easier or harder. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Coming up in tomorrow‚Äôs post: How carbs affect your energy, satiety, and appetite.

Carbohydrates (aka ‚Äúcarbs‚Äù) have gotten a bad reputation lately, of with people who don‚Äôt really understand what carbs are. The role that carbohydrates are best known for is providing energy to the body. In order to function, every single cell in your body needs energy. For example, even the cells in your eyeballs need energy or they will disintegrate. Carbohydrates are one of the 3 main categories of nutrients that your body can break down to use for energy (the others are fat and protein), and the amount of energy in food can be measured in calories (more calories = more energy). *
*
Technically, carbohydrates can be classified into 3 main types: (1) Simple carbohydrates or sugars are small molecules of carbohydrates. Examples include table sugar, lactose in milk, and fructose.
(2) Complex carbohydrates are sugars that are linked together to form larger molecules. Examples include any form of starch, such as the starch found in white rice and bread.
(3) Fibre is technically also a complex carbohydrate but is unique in that humans cannot digest it (which is partly why you poop more if you eat more fibre). It is found in high amounts in vegetables, fruits, legumes, and whole grains. *
*
Individual foods often contain a combination of sugars, starches, and fibre. A banana is a great example of this: Greener bananas contain more starch which slowly turns into sugar as they ripen (sweeter means more sugar), and the fibre gives them structure. Some foods will contain one form of carbohydrate more than the others. For example, table sugar is pure sugar with no complex carbohydrates, while the carbs in white rice are almost entirely starch.
*
*

caption:
Going to the gym like it's 2021!

I was just starting to regularly attend practice with my Olympic lifting club again when the Covid-19 situation hit. Recently, my coach @anthony.agtarap decided to set up a Zoom call during the group training time so he could watch us lift in our home gyms (or in the case of @gdotyee, his living room haha). He was able to give us feedback on the spot, and together we all had a few laughs.

I must admit, I was really not up for lifting today but I had made the commitment and I knew my coach would follow up if I didn't show up. I was also glad to see my fellow team mates. 
The internet allows us many options to stay connected and still get fitness/sport coaching while we practice social distancing. Excited to see how we use technology more and more to make things more convenient!

caption:
No gym (#kettlebell)? No problem. 
As much as I love the windmill exercise, I love this variation even more: the bent press! I love it because it gives all the benefits of the windmill (whole-body mobility and stability) BUT allows you to use a heavier weight since you don't have to use your upper body to lift the weight (instead, you get underneath the weight). Using a heavier weight challenges everything even more. Typically, this exercise is done with a kettlebell, but no reason why you can't improvise!

One thing I discovered about myself when doing this exercise is that even though my right arm is stronger than my left (especially for standard overhead/pressing exercises), the shoulder felt noticeably less stable than the left during this exercise. This was because the end of my right upper arm bone was not as well centered in its socket (i.e. my right shoulder was slouched forward), which is actually pretty common in this modern world. Once I pulled my shoulder back to a better position, it felt more stable.

Thanks to @ironkimono for introducing this exercise!

We know exercise is important, but it is particularly important when you do shift work. Having a reversed and irregular sleep pattern because you work at night is going against your biology, and has negative impacts on cardiovascular, mental, and metabolic health. The World Health Organization considers shift work as a probable carcinogen. Health care workers make this sacrifice to support everyone else, so it's important we help them optimize their lifestyle in any way we can. 
This pandemic situation has given me more time to think about how to better support the health and fitness of healthcare workers given my training in kinesiology and nutrition. That is why I‚Äôm putting together a brand-new program starting Monday March 30th. This is specifically for front-line health care workers (e.g. nurses, care aides, paramedics, community support workers, and other healthcare workers) who want to lose 1-2 inches off their waist, get stronger, and have more energy in 60 days. It‚Äôs a remote program, so you can join from anywhere in the world.

I‚Äôm looking for 5 people to test it out at a HUGE DISCOUNT, help me work out the kinks, and get amazing results that I can use as a case study. If that‚Äôs you, message me with ‚Äòtell me more‚Äô and I‚Äôll share details about this exciting program.

Being able to lift heavy weight is not enough. Everyone should do some sort of a single leg exercise to keep the body healthy. This is important if you're a health care worker handling patients as it reduces your risk of low back injuries, which were common amongst the health care workers I've helped. Correct form involves:

- Keeping the pelvis level (one side should not be higher than the other).
- Feeling the glutes and back of the legs doing most of the work.

Getting strong vs. getting "bulky"
*
*
Being stronger makes life easier. Did you know that you can get stronger without necessarily getting bigger muscles? That's because strength is not just based on muscle size, but also the ability for the brain to call on the muscle to do work. *
Think of this: When you learn to play an instrument, it's not because your muscles got bigger to help you have the strength to play it. Instead, it's because you improved the coordination of your body. Coordination applies to your ability to express strength as well, and just like with learning to play the piano, strength improves with practice.
*
A lot of women (and even men) don't want to lift weights because they don't want to "get bulky". In reality, it takes either a lot of work or a decent amount of body fat to look bulky. This is a photo of a 2016 gold medalist, Sopita Tanasan. She weighed 48kg (106 lbs) and is shown her snatching 92 kg--almost double her body weight, and far more than what bigger people can lift.
*
To increase strength without growing the muscles significantly, train with heavier weight and fewer reps and sets. caption:
üî•Turns out, teamwork really DOES make the dream work! üëØ‚Äç‚ôÇ‚ÄçI love this study! It shows how people are more apt to have self control when they depend on each other ‚Ä¶ even first-graders! üßíHere‚Äôs what happened: researchers paired up 5- and 6-year-olds and had them play toss with each other. Then, they put each partner in a separate room, and put a cookie in front of them. üç™The kids were told that if they waited 15 minutes to eat the cookie, they‚Äôd get another cookie as a reward. üç™üç™But ‚Ä¶ some of the kids were told that they‚Äôd get the second cookie only if both they and their partner ‚Äì who they couldn‚Äôt see! ‚Äì waited to eat the first cookie! üíïCompared to kids who weren‚Äôt told about the other kids, the ones who knew their friends were depending on them (and vice versa) were less apt to eat the first cookie. ü§úü§õPretty cool, huh? Just shows the power of having accountability and social support!

REFERENCE:
www.psychologicalscience.org/news/releases/marshmallow-test-redux-new-research-reveals-children-show-better-self-control-when-they-depend-on-each-other.html

caption:
‚ö°With all the news about the coronavirus pandemic, it‚Äôs easy to feel powerless over your health.
üçéBut there actually are some steps you can take to help your immune system in top shape. üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÇ‚ÄçTaking action goes a LONG way toward moving you from overwhelmed to empowered.
ü•¶I‚Äôve got a list of healthy immune-boosting actions you can take to get back that sense of control. 
NOTE: Remember, it‚Äôs still super important to follow prevention guidelines for handwashing and avoiding people who are sick ‚Ä¶. even if you follow these steps!
‚óè	Get enough sleep. This can help improve your body‚Äôs natural immune function. Aim for 7-8 hours a night.
‚óè	Keep up with your fitness routine. Moderate to intense workouts lasting under an hour help boost your immune system both immediately and in the long run. ‚óè	Cut back on your stress with scheduled downtime and breathing exercises. Chronic stress appears to wear down your immune system, which can make you more vulnerable to illness. ‚óè	Eat a healthy & balanced diet that‚Äôs low in sugar: A balanced diet that contains veggies, fruits, and healthy fats is rich in antioxidants and micronutrients that support your immune system.
‚óè	Stay hydrated. Drinking enough water makes it easier for your cells to do their job ‚Äì plus allows your body to more easily process food and eliminate waste. Shoot for at least 8 8-ounce (240 ml) glasses a day.

I previously wrote about the overlooked barriers that nurses, care-aides, paramedics and other healthcare support workers face in terms of staying healthy (http://silviahua.com/the-neglected-aspect-of-nurse-and-hospital-worker-health-and-safety/)
*
*
Now that I myself have more free time due to a pause on all in-person personal training sessions, I'd like to finally work on this project that has been on my mind for a couple years: Helping these patient-facing healthcare workers take care of their own health, and do their work with less effort and pain. *

MYTH-BUSTING POST
üßêü§ØThere is so much misinformation being spread about the coronavirus, it can be HUGELY helpful to consult an official source.
I stumbled across this fantastic ‚Äúmyth-buster‚Äù page by the World Health Organization. It‚Äôs definitely worth checking out.
Among other things:
‚ùÑ‚òÄüå°Climate/temperature doesn‚Äôt affect the virus
ü¶üIt isn‚Äôt transmitted by mosquito bites.
üí°UV lights aren‚Äôt a good way to kill the virus.
üíäAntibiotics won‚Äôt help fight the virus.
üõÄHot baths are ineffective in preventing illness onset.
Now you know!!! Here‚Äôs the link: www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/myth-busters
‚û° Handwashing, avoiding contact with sick people, and limiting your exposure to crowds appears to be the best way to go.

SHOE-FREE ZONE
üí°üõãHere‚Äôs a simple (and cozy!) way to eliminate some germs and bacteria from your home: make it a shoe-free zone!
üëûIn the wake of the coronavirus pandemic, a lot of us are paying more attention to our exposure to harmful germs and bacteria.
üëüFor centuries, people in some cultures have avoided wearing shoes in their homes, and if you‚Äôre Chinese like me, it‚Äôs the norm. It only makes sense, because our shoes can track in anything they‚Äôve been exposed to out in the world, and studies have shown they actually can be dirtier than a toilet.
Yuck, right?
üö™ü•æIf you‚Äôre thinking of making your home shoe-free, set up a spot to store shoes as soon as people come in the door, with a chair nearby that makes it easy to put on/take off footwear. üë†Then, clean your floors to get rid of loose dirt and mop with a warm solution of mild disinfectant that‚Äôs designed for your flooring.
‚úÖThat way, your feet will be less likely to pick bacteria that are lingering after being tracked in by your shoes.
REFERENCE:
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2019/07/03/my-shoes-dirty-studies-suggest-theyre-covered-fecal-bacteria/1637780001/
https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/house-and-home/household-advice/a31344990/coronavirus-clean-germs-viruses/

What's the point of personal training if it's not every week?

Many people don't sign up for personal training because they feel they can reach their goals on their own. I did not have any reservations about you as a trainer, we talked before and I felt very comfortable that you know what you're talking. Mostly I had reservations about how much value I could get from single sessions, because I knew I wouldn't be signing up for ongoing training.

caption:
‚ùìMYTH OR FACT? ‚ùì ü§îYou should skip your pre-workout static stretches because now scientists say it might interfere with your performance. üôà
.
üôâ
.
üôä
üî•FACT üî•! üí™We used to believe that stretching before your workout was a big part of avoiding injury, but it turns out it‚Äôs actually NOT. üëâResearchers believe that stretching before a workout can tire out your muscles before you get to the part where you‚Äôre actually doing work!* üí°Instead it‚Äôs a good idea to warm up before you work out by doing ‚Äúbig‚Äù dynamic movements that mimic what‚Äôs going to happen you in your workout or other dynamic flexibility exercises which a skilled movement professional can customize for you. üëçTHE TAKEAWAY: Stretch your body‚Äôs major muscle groups AFTER your workout when your muscles are warm, or at another point during the day, at least 2-3x a week. üëüIs a dynamic warm-up already part of your workout prep?! Any questions? Let me know below ... * Note: Certain static stretches may be beneficial to help you get into better positions during exercises. To know which ones are best for you so you make the best use of your time, get professional help from a good personal trainer or coach.

REFERENCES:
www.webmd.com/fitness-exercise/features/how-to-stretch
https://journals.lww.com/acsm-healthfitness/fulltext/2016/09000/flexibility_exercises_and_performance.4.aspx

üí•I have a tip for you today that will help you relax, soothe your muscles AND keep you warm. üß¶üß£It‚Äôs a homemade heating pad, using just three things ‚Ä¶ uncooked rice, a large sock, and, if you‚Äôre feeling crafty, a ribbon or string to tie the sock shut (or you can just tie a knot in the sock!). üåæThe amount of uncooked rice you‚Äôll need depends on the size of the sock you‚Äôre using as well as how flexible you want your homemade heating pad to be. ‚òÄ I personally like mine to be pretty flexible, so it will fit easily around my neck or shoulders if I‚Äôm trying to target those areas.

You‚Äôll want to get any kind of rice EXCEPT processed ‚Äúinstant‚Äù rice, because it will crumble with use.

All you have to do to make your heating pad is pour the rice into the sock until you reach your desired length/flexibility, and then tie it shut. üå∫Note: If you want a more soothing experience, add a few drops of pure organic peppermint or lavender essential oil to the rice and mix it well before adding it to the sock. üí°To use your new heating pad, simply place it in the microwave for 1-2 minutes depending on the wattage of your microwave.

When it‚Äôs heated to your desired temp, simply wrap your DIY heating pad around the area you want to target and let it do its job. 
These can be reused over and over again.

caption:
üí•Time to get REAL. Do you ever have those days when you are working on a new goal or creating a new habit ‚Ä¶ and you just feel OVER it? üí¢ üôÖ‚Äç‚ôÄ‚ÄçYour willpower is slipping and you are ready to say to heck with it? It‚Äôs time to HALT ‚Ä¶ and borrow a powerful method from the recovery movement. üõë

When you feel like letting go of your healthy new habit, chances are 1 of 4 feelings (or maybe a combo of ALL of them!) are affecting you. ü•¥üò¥That is where the word HALT comes in ‚Äì you might be Hungry, Angry, Lonely, or Tired. ü§Øüò£ We don‚Äôt make the best decisions when we feel any of those things. That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs such a good idea to step back for a minute or two. üõëDo a little scan of your current situation to find out what‚Äôs REALLY going on ... and then take action to fix the underlying cause! ‚úåAs in: eat a healthy snack, meditate, take a walk (outside if possible) to get a fresh perspective, reach out to a supportive friend or family member, or even take a nap or go to bed early!

It is absolutely AMAZING what a difference it can make to HALT (literally and figuratively!) when you feel like giving up. It gives you a chance to look a little deeper to figure out why you‚Äôre feeling the way you are, and then take care of yourself. ‚≠ê(And be super proud of yourself in the process!) #doyouevenlift #gainz #vancouver #yvr #fitness  #nutrition #nutritioncoach #personaltrainer

‚≠êWhat do YOU do to stay positive? ü§©Study after study shows how having a positive attitude can help you across all aspects of your life ‚Äì including keeping your heart healthy! üíì

That‚Äôs super important because heart disease is the number one cause of death in the US (also in Australia and Europe!). üí°Some of us are just naturally more positive than others ‚Ä¶ but there are things you can do to reframe your mindset so that you help shrug off those negative emotions. üëâChange your perspective: Practice slowing down and enjoying the moment, vs. rushing to get through things. This is actually a skill you can learn over time.

If your plans get changed or something gets in the way of what you had planned, try to look at it from a different viewpoint. Is there something good that can come from it? (Also, recognize that change is part of life.) üëâSmile! Even when you don‚Äôt feel like it. 
One study showed that smiling (even if it‚Äôs fake) can reduce your blood pressure and your heart rate. üëâTake action. If something is truly bugging you, take action to do something about it. This will help you feel more in control (and positive!) about your situation. üí°Remember this: ACTION alleviates anxiety.

Check out this article by Johns Hopkins for even more info about the power of positive thinking on your health: www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/wellness-and-prevention/the-power-of-positive-thinking
üò¥üõèDo you take naps?! üõã

caption:
üî•Just came across two interesting tidbits about goal-setting that can have an impact on how you feel mentally ‚Ä¶ and also your likelihood of actually achieving your goals! ‚ú®First: You should actually WANT to achieve the goal. Too many times we go after certain goals because we THINK we should ‚Ä¶ not because we actually want to. üí°If you‚Äôre feeling lukewarm about your goal, do some thinking into WHY you feel that way. üëâIf it‚Äôs still something that you NEED (even if you don‚Äôt want to do it), then try a REFRAME. This could include focusing on the payoff vs. the time/work it will take to make it happen. 
It could be focused on what life will be like AFTER you reach your goal, rather than on the temporary discomfort you may experience to get there. ‚úÖSecond: Be as specific as absolutely possible. Instead of ‚Äúeat clean,‚Äù this could be ‚Äúeat 3 to 5 servings of vegetables every day‚Äù or ‚Äúeliminate added sugar.‚Äù üëâInteresting fact, one study showed that people who focused on more specific goals felt less depression and psychological distress!

If you want more research-backed tips on smart goal setting, check this out: 
www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/supersurvivors/201902/5-tips-setting-healthy-goals

Have a tip you use to reach one of YOUR goals? Share it with me below!

caption:
üí°Here is a quick goal-setting tip! üíØ üëâInstead of setting a goal around something you don‚Äôt have direct control over, switch it up to something you CAN control. üí•And that‚Äôs your habits, your actions, and your performance! üèÜFor instance, if you have a body composition goal (i.e., you want to change your weight or your clothing size), you can‚Äôt directly control that. ‚úÖBut what you can control are the ACTIONS you take to get there ‚Äì so make those actions your goals!

That means instead of focusing on that 20 pounds you want to lose ... you focus on prioritizing your workouts, and you have a solid plan for what your food looks like for the week. üî•The same thing goes with anything related to health, career, relationships/hobbies, finances, etc. ‚ú®Sounds so simple, but it makes a MAJOR difference!

ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èIf you know me you know I can‚Äôt live without my blue blocking glasses.
*
*
‚û° Here‚Äôs why: Having sufficient, good quality sleep is one of the most important things you can do for your health. Melatonin is a hormone your body produces in the evening to help you fall asleep and stay asleep, but its production is suppressed by the blue light emitted from our indoor lighting, not to mention our smartphones and computes. Wearing blue blocking glasses (available on Amazon) filters out blue light so you can restore your body's natural ability to create melatonin and thus get better sleep.
*
*
For me, it‚Äôs a definite must-have (even when other people see me, such as during this party my mom threw for me)! I put it on when I get home, or sometimes even on my way home after training/work. Do you have any ‚Äúmust-haves‚Äù in your daily life?
