üôåWhat are you scared of? ‚ù§Ô∏è üò®I came across an article about a woman who felt like she was scared of pretty much EVERYTHING: the doctor, heights, dogs, driving ‚Ä¶ and even getting older. üò±

The same day I heard a completely different story about a man who moved to the US to start a company, but failed miserably on his first try. üòñ

He was devastated and it almost crushed him. After some self-reflection, he realized it wasn‚Äôt the failure, but his crippling fear of rejection‚Ä¶ that was preventing him from living his life again üò£

These two people didn‚Äôt know each other, but they both decided to take the same course of action. 
They were tired of being held back by the fears ‚Ä¶ so they decided to rush headfirst into them! 
Each challenged themselves to do what scared them, for 100 days straight. 
They stepped way outside their comfort zones to do things like rappelling, walking in the subway in their bathing suit, or touching giant, hairy spiders. ü§∫One by one, they faced their fears. In the process, they learned they were capable of SO MUCH MORE than they ever imagined! ü§úü§õThis is so inspiring and empowering. üôå Our society has it all wrong. We like to think of brave people as having no fear ‚Äì but the truth is, you can‚Äôt be brave unless you have fear! 
Without it, there is nothing to overcome.

After her 100 days, the woman started a business to help others (http://100dayswithoutfear.com/), and the the man wrote a book about his rejection quest: www.amazon.com/Rejection-Proof-Became-Invincible-Through/dp/080414138X/) What‚Äôs ONE THING you can do today to further your LIFE in the direction you want to head? üì¢ I‚Äôd love to hear about it! Let me know below ...

‚òÄ I love this time of the year, because people are so EXCITED to create real change in their fitness & wellness! üëçI‚Äôm so grateful to be able to help in any way possible. This is WHY I do what I do! 
I became interested in nutrition after I started competing in Olympic lifting and wanted to both optimize performance and get into the 48kg weight class. This interest developed into a passion after the severe food restriction and weight obsession lead to some serious health issues (I may look healthy in the photo, but I was not). That led to me taking the leap into getting my level 2 nutrition coaching certification with Precision Nutrition, which brought me to where I am today, helping everyday busy professionals find nutrition strategies to support their fitness goals without counting every calorie. Reaching goals isn't simply about knowing what to do, but actually finding ways to do the right actions consistently (easier said than done!). ü§©Now, all these years later, I still get fired up when I get to help a new client map out their goal-getting journey with a combination of smart, sustainable exercise and nutrition. What inspires YOUR fitness/wellness journey? Let me know below‚Ä¶ I‚Äôd love to know!

If a task seems daunting, just take the first step. Often I do not feel like exercising, and what gets me through knowing that if all I do is one set of one exercise, it will be better than nothing. Almost always, once I finish that set, I realize it wasn't so bad and can do the next set.

‚úãüôÉRaise your hand if you want more happiness in your life! ü§© üíÉüèΩ I have some amazing news that can help with that ‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs all about how exercise can actually make you feel HAPPIER ‚Äì both immediately and in the long-term. üï∫ üèãüèø‚Äç‚ôÇ‚Äç FIRST ‚Äì people who get at least 30 minutes of exercise most days of the week are 30% more likely to say they feel happier vs. those who don‚Äôt ‚Ä¶ and it doesn‚Äôt matter what kind of exercise they do! 
It could be yoga, jogging, or anything in between. This finding was part of a major review of 23 published studies into the connection between happiness and exercise, including people from basically every age, ethnicity and socioeconomic status. üßòüèº‚Äç‚ôÄ‚Äç Note: researchers still found higher ‚Äúhappiness scores‚Äù even in those who just worked out 1-2x a week. üèÉüèª‚Äç‚ôÄ‚Äç SECOND ‚Äì getting a cardio workout can help inoculate you against a bad mood for up to 12 hours!

According to research done at the University of Vermont, getting a 20-minute moderate-intensity workout in can boost your mood for hours ‚Äì helping you to more easily shrug off stress. ü§∏üèæ‚Äç‚ôÄ‚Äç ü§ó The takeaway: Try getting in a workout if you want to bust stress, beat a bad mood, or create more happiness in your life!

Want even more info? Check this out: www.acefitness.org/education-and-resources/lifestyle/blog/7395/exercise-your-way-to-happiness

‚û° I have 2 scary facts for you ... üíî 1. The more ‚Äúultra-processed‚Äù foods you eat, the more likely you are to do worse on heart-health tests.
üò≤ 2. Most of us get more than 50% of our daily calories from ultra-processed foods! ‚ò£ ‚ÄúUltra-processed‚Äù foods are basically grab & go manufactured foods ‚Äì processed meats, chicken nuggets, soft drinks, cookies & cakes, chips, etc. ‚Äì that contain unhealthy fats, starches, added sugar, and artificial flavors, dyes, and emulsifiers. üçüüç© üíî Scientists from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found that for every 5% jump in calories from ultra-processed foods, people‚Äôs cardiovascular health dropped!

So, adults who ate approximately 70% of their calories from ultra-processed foods were half as likely to have "ideal" cardiovascular health, as defined by the American Heart Association‚Äôs guidelines.

That‚Äôs compared with people who ate 40% or less of their calories from ultra-processed 
foods. üçéü•¶The takeaway: choose WHOLE ‚ÄúREAL‚Äù FOODS instead of food products that come in a package! This means lean proteins, lots of veggies & fruits, healthy natural fats, and unprocessed grains. üçè

This info comes from the US National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, which contained info from 13,446 adults age 20 or older, who completed a 24-hour dietary recall and answered questions about their cardiovascular health.

You can learn more here:
http://ow.ly/SCIl50xoJni

Posted @withrepost ‚Ä¢ @dr.jacob.harden ACTIVE vs PASSIVE : WHEN & WHY?
.
There are a lot of strategies you can use to improve upon range of motion. The range from more general to more specific and from passive to active.
.
Passive strategies for the most part lead to increases in passive ROM. So if you are looking just for some more flexibility in general, they may suffice.
.
Active strategies are used to develop strength, control, and coordination in new ranges of motion. So if you are seeking to improve upon your ability to actively access a ROM via muscular force, then an active strategy would work well.
.
Specific strategies seek to isolate one particular range of motion. While general ones look to develop more global range of motion increases.
.
To put some examples here...
üîπ Foam rolling = Passive / General
üîπ Static stretching = Passive / Specific
üîπ Dynamic warm up = Active / General
üîπ End range training = Active / Specific
.
Which you use really depends on your personal needs and what you feel provides the best results.
.
For example, I find that hip internal rotation responds much better to active strategies than passive ones. Hence me showing an end range training option here.
.
But improving ankle dorsiflexion with a passive approach often suffices.
.
So as you scroll the gram and see unlimited amounts of mobility drills, always be thinking about why you want it in the first place, and that will help you reduce what the best approach is to get it.
.
Tag a friend with stiff hips and share the wealth!
.

caption: Okay, so Canadian Thanksgiving is over, but any time is a good time to review what you're grateful for as well as challenge your brain with a fun puzzle.

3 minute paleo almond protein mug cake!

Posted @withrepost ‚Ä¢ @sugarfree.recipes

Here‚Äôs the microwave version of our low-carb, high protein ‚Äúcake‚Äù that‚Äôs ready in just 3 minutes! The recipe shown contains under 140 calories and 9g protein and is best consumed warm.

Ingredients:
- 1 egg
- 6 g (1 tbsp) @pb.and.me sugar-free powdered almond butter
- 2 tsp Westpoint Naturals monk fruit powder or equivalent of another sweetener
- 1 tsp oil (we like avocado oil as it is healthy and flavourless)

1. Blend all the ingredients in a blender for 1 minute. 
2. Pour batter into a mug.
3. Microwave for ~45sec on medium power until cooked through (i.e. an inserted fork comes out clean). Photo shows one batch, blended with an immersion blender. You can also make multiple batches. If using a standard blender, you will probably need to at least double the recipe to get sufficient volume for the blender to blend it properly.

Easy paleo almond protein cupcakes!

Posted @withrepost ‚Ä¢ @sugarfree.recipes

Here‚Äôs a low-carb, high protein ‚Äúcupcake‚Äù that can be prepped in just 2 minutes with just 4 ingredients! The recipe shown contains under 140 calories and 9g protein and is best consumed warm.

Ingredients:
- 1 egg
- 6 g (1 tbsp) @pb.and.me sugar-free powdered almond butter
- 2 tsp Westpoint Naturals monk fruit powder or equivalent of another sweetener
- 1 tsp oil (we like avocado oil as it is healthy and flavourless)

1. Blend all the ingredients in a blender for 1 minute. 
2. Pour batter into 1 or 2 muffin cups, depending on your preferred size.
3. Bake in a toaster oven at 335 deg F for 5-8 minutes, or until a toothpick comes out clean.

This recipe is best consumed while warm. Photo shows one batch, blended with an immersion blender and baked into 2 small cupcakes. You can also make multiple batches and/or divide the batter into fewer larger cupcakes. If using a standard blender, you will probably need to at least double the recipe to get sufficient volume for the blender to blend it properly.

Golden milk, which gets its colour from tumeric, has been consumed for thousands of years for its many health benefits. Here‚Äôs how you can easily make a version that is sugar-free, low-calorie, and vegan!

*

Here‚Äôs a refreshing summer soda that also happens to be sugar-free and full of the benefits of ginger and lemon:

Ingredients:
* 1 cup of club soda, sparkling water, or water
* 1 tbsp of lemon juice
* 3 tsp Westpoint Naturals monk fruit powder or other sweetener
* 1 pinch of ground ginger
* (optional) ice

Mix the ground ginger, monk fruit powder, and lemon juice. Add ice and club soda. Stir and enjoy! Keep stirring occasionally as it is normal for the ginger and monk fruit powder to settle to the bottom.

caption:
Not glamourous or exciting, but still a new PR. The other day, for the first time ever perhaps, I did more than 12 squats‚ÄîI did 20 goblet squats with 28kg! Since 2017 (my last hypertrophy phase), I haven‚Äôt squatted more than 6 consecutive reps. *
*
Over a year ago, I decided to shift away from prioritizing strength and competing in weightlifting to prioritizing my career and health. As someone identified strongly with being a weightlifter, letting go of this has been psychologically difficult. Not pushing my strength limits in training and spending less time training less means I cannot expect to break any 1 rep max (or 2-5RM) personal records, and breaking personal records is what makes training rewarding for me. However, I realized there are still many personal records to be made and broken. And that is what I am going to do, starting with rep maximums beyond 6 reps and even AMRAPs. *
*
How can YOU stay motivated to train when life makes it hard to do so? My goal is to help people find ways to keep doing what helps them move well and stay strong. *
*

Particularly when exercising, it is important to keep this in mind and fuel accordingly around exercise sessions. What are your favourite healthy sources of carbohydrates around exercise sessions?  #doyouevenlift #gainz #protein #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #carbs #veggies

Relaxin‚Äô!
*
Why is it important for women to train the muscles during pregnancy? Relaxin. No, it's not just a lyric in the Fresh Prince of Bel-Air song. *
Relaxin is a hormone that increases during pregnancy to allow the body to adapt to the growing baby and the pelvis to widen during labour. The downside of relaxin is that it causes all the joints to become more flexible so injuries are more likely to happen, even in positions that were previously safe. The sacroiliac joints in the low back/pelvis are commonly problematic, resulting in low back pain or instability during walking/lunging movements.
*
How do you project the joints when relaxin makes the joints looser? Train the muscles to compensate. Afraid of getting "bulky"? Keeping the body and joints stable is often a matter of coordinating and "waking up" the muscles; in the same way you don't need big muscles to balance on one foot, you don't need big muscles to keep your joints stable and injury-free.
#doyouevenlift #gainz #yvr #fitness #womenwholift

caption:
This post was inspired by my friend and nutrition coaching client, Pamela. 
Breakfast is the meal that likely has the most opportunity for improvement. A complete meal should consist of these 4 components:
	1. Protein (1 portion = size of your palm, or ~20g of protein)
	2. Vegetables (1 portion = size of your fist)
	3. Smart Carbohydrates (1 portion = one cupped handful)
	4. Healthy fat (1 portion = thumb-sized portion of a food or 2 teaspoons of oil)

Common breakfasts, even "healthy" ones, typically provide plenty of carbohydrates (e.g. breads, oats, cereal, pastries, fruit) but often lack protein (even one cup of milk or one serving of regular yogurt has ~8g of protein) and vegetables. Protein helps keep you feel longer and help you have fewer cravings later in the day. Vegetables are rich in micro-nutrients which have many benefits, and the fiber also keeps you full longer, so why miss this opportunity to consume more vegetables, which most people don't eat enough of anyway?

Here are some options for quick breakfasts that provide a bit more protein and vegetables.
1. Leftovers or whatever you're packing for lunch. Who says you have to eat "breakfast foods" at breakfast?
2. Hardboiled eggs with fruit and raw veggies. The eggs can be made ahead of time.
	3. Baked eggs. I like baking because it's a cooking method that you can set and forget without risking burning down the house. You can also make a baked frittata by mixing in veggies, spices, and meat. Once cooked, it's good for a few days in the fridge and can be eaten without heating.
	4. Plain Greek yogurt or cottage cheese with fruit. Bananas or frozen fruit are super easy.
	5. A super smoothie which includes all the 4 meal components listed above (Bonus: If you want me to email you an awesome resource on how to make a super smoothie with example ingredients, email me with the subject "smoothie"): a. Protein: Greek yogurt, protein powder, cottage cheese, or sugar-free powdered peanut or almond butter. 	b. Vegetables: Spinach, kale, or whatever you like! A powdered greens supplement will also do. 	c. Carbohydrates: Any fruit, or even cooked pumpkin or legumes (I used to put banana and cooked lentils in

Golden hazelnut cappuccino: Calcium, turmeric, and hazelnutty goodness in a cup, ready in just one minute. *
*
Ingredients:
- 1/2 cup of whole goat milk (regular milk works too)
- 1/4 tsp turmeric
- 1/2 tsp pure monk fruit powder or another sweetening agent for sweetness (Westpoint Naturals is the only brand I've found that doesn't mix it with other sweeteners)
- 2 tsp/4 g of @pb.and.me powdered hazelnut butter
- dash of black pepper
- optional: dash of cinnamon and/or vanilla
*
*
Directions:
Heat the milk using a milk frother with the cappuccino whisk. While the milk is frothing, mix the remaining ingredients in a splash of water. Pour in the frothed milk and enjoy. *
*
All the above items except for the milk can be found on Amazon.

#HealthTip: Keep a log of your health consultations and issues.
*
*
At my first provincial weightlifting meet in 2015, I dropped the barbell and it landed on my back. I thought the only issue that the impact caused was a painful low back which went away after a couple weeks without any treatment. Turns out that some of the neck and thoracic spine issues I experienced months and years later were likely caused by the not just the impact of the barbell, but from the consequent movement of the neck. I'm glad this lift was caught on video because it was my athletic therapist, @mcconaghydarren at Coastal Therapy that helped me make that connection and treat my neck/spine issues.
I saw in my notes that the two separate neck strains occurred after the date of this event. I keep a record of my various body symptoms and notes from discussions with my medical providers. This allows me to better take care of my health and not rely on memory. It also helps my health care team to get a better picture of what may be going on. 
#doyouevenlift #gainz #vancouver #yvr #fitness #snatch #weightlifting

caption:
Life is not about fitness and training.

Yes, that's right. As passionate as I am about helping people feel good in their bodies through movement and nutrition, I don't think people are lazy if they don't live a healthy lifestyle. It's perfectly okay to for career, family, volunteer, and other things to come first. Exercise and healthy eating should not take away from other priorities, but enhance it. 
It's easy for sports coaches and fitness professionals to label people as lazy or unmotivated if they don't meet a certain standard of physical activity. Not only does this perspective hinder the coach's ability to help promote exercise/sport, but it is often untrue. 
What makes it hard for you to exercise and eat healthily, and what support do you need?

#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #personaltrainer #equinox #coach

caption:
Sleep your way to a fitter body. *
*
Yesterday at work, I was wondering why I had higher cravings than normal for sweet and starchy foods. Luckily, I had banana and peanut butter on hand and managed to resist the temptation to buy food. I then remembered that I only slept 3 hours the previous night and how sleep deprivation results in higher than normal cravings for carbohydrates.
*
*
A few things happen that is a lose-lose situation for body shape when we are sleep deprived:
- Appetite-regulating hormones become messed, resulting in food cravings.
- Insulin sensitivity becomes messed, meaning the body's ability to regulate blood sugar and other metabolic processes becomes messed.
- We don't want to move as much, further reducing our ability to handle dietary carbohydrates and fat in a healthy way.
*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #carbohydrates

caption:

I have to remind myself that sometimes, when people act in ways that aren't particularly nice, it's because they may be dealing with things and may be simply projecting that to others. For example, many people assume that work is a chore and is incompatible with joy.  Or maybe they assume everyone works a 9-5 job. 
I'm lucky to have found work that is gives me lots of meaning. I'd trade that for drinking away my stress any day.

caption:
I did some cardio on the assault bike today (flashbacks from being an unfit kid in PE class!) thanks to the coaches at @powerspeedendurance. They taught us that DECREASING expiration during exercise actually improves aerobic energy production because the accumulation of carbon dioxide helps with oxygen extraction by the muscles (this totally makes sense if you know about the Bohr effect in physiology)! Never thought about how simply manipulating breathing in a way that which DECREASES short-term performance could lead to longterm aerobic enhancement.
*
*
They will be hosting a seminar this Sunday at @engineeredbodies for anyone wants to learn more about their concepts. *
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness

caption:
I have a long history of doing #deepsquats!
Last weekend, I attended a workshop by @pronatalfitness on how to train pre-and post-natal women. I loved their "performance-based" approach on pregnancy and motherhood: both have very high, specific physical demands on the mother's body, just like any athletic event. If athletes do specific, high-intensity physical preparation for their sport, then why shouldn't expectant and new moms do specific, high-intensity physical preparation to prepare their bodies for  carrying an extra 25+ lbs in their abdomen, pushing a baby out, and lifting/carrying a baby with one arm while doing other things the other arm? Simply "taking it easy" with exercise is not particularly helpful. *
*
This approach to exercise before/after pregnancy is similar to the approach I used when helping injured workers return to work: You have to train/rehabilitate the stabilizer muscles, train job-specific tasks (e.g. carrying heavy weight on one shoulder), as well as just GET STRONG! Performance-based training is not just for sports athletes. It's for life.
*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #vancouver #yvr #fitness

caption:
Non-compliance. *
Every time I feel resistance as a patient/client, I reflect on how my own coaching practice and whether I have been effective at helping my clients.
*
My job as a kinesiologist and personal trainer involves recommending exercises to clients. I've seen three different physical/athletic therapists for help to optimize my own movement and address issues, and they each recommended exercises for me to do to address what I went to see them for. Even though I literally paid these therapists to provide me this guidance, I found it hard to do the recommended exercises long-term since they weren't exactly exciting exercises and they ate into my workout time. *
What's the minimum effective dose, or the one thing that will reap the biggest reward? This is something we should all strive to think about instead of thinking in all-or-nothing terms.
*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness

It takes time, consistency, constant assessment, and prescription of appropriate progressions.  There will never be one exercise that will do it all. caption:
Wipe the slate (plate?) clean

Every day is a new day. Every moment is a new opportunity to make a decision which moves you in the direction you want, no matter what the past decisions were.

People who approach food with a restrictive mindset or who assign morals to foods (i.e. "good" and "bad:" foods) are more likely to experience bingeing once they do get a bite of the restricted/bad food. Scientists call this disinhibition, but it is also known colloquially as the "f*** it" phenomenon. 
Next time you feel guilt for eating in a way that is not aligned with your intentions/goals, remember that continuing down that path just because you already "screwed up" would be like poking a hole in all your car tires just because one of them is flat.
*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness

2019 is here. It is the year I am focused on my recovery more so than making gainz. In the past, I sacrificed sleep to fit in my gym training and in the process, made very little strength progress for all those hours. The poor recovery and sleep deprivation made getting through the day pretty miserable. Nowadays, I recommend to anyone looking to lose fat, get strong, and/or gain muscle to priortize sleep before training more. Don‚Äôt listen to those who tell you that sleeping means you‚Äôre lazy. How do you protect your sleep? *
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness

That time I became the person on the medal (but with a much lighter barbell). Fiber is important, folks. Thanks to Herman Chan for capturing the moment.  #doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #weightlifting

Care homes. I've been to many of them as that is where many of my rehab clients work as care aides or other similar professionals. It's a tough job. As much as I know that having a stronger body would protect these women from injury, I don't blame these women for not doing resistance training. Shift work, low income, being immigrants, and being women are just some of the psycho-social barriers that make it tough to maintain a strong body that moves well. This is why I now think about how to make good movement/resistance training and nutrition realistic in the context of people who need the most help. How can the work place actually promote resilient healthy bodies and not just accident prevention? How can we help individuals not just know what they should do, but actually do it? #doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #workplace #workplacehealth #ohs #worksafe #worksafebc #internationalwomensday

Oatmeal doesn't have to be plain or sweet--it can be savoury too! I batch cook oats in a slow cooker and eat it chilled with salt/soy sauce and protein. Sometimes, I mix in spinach once it's done slow cooking for a hassle-free way to incorporate veggies.

For extra flavour, you can cook it in homemade broth.
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #protein #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #carbs #lazycooking #veggies

The more you know, the more you know that there so much more you DON'T know. *
*
How do you get fitter? Exercise. How do you get leaner? Eat less junk and don't overeat. How do you feel more energized? Get good quality sleep! So what's stopping people? What's stopping you from achieving your goals?*
*
With so many potential topics to learn about as I continue my career in health and fitness, I've decided to focus my professional development on the big rock: behaviour change. If knowledge was all that was needed to achieve what we want, we'd all be as rich and fit as we want. Less experienced/effective coaches, including myself before I became more self aware, care more about showing others how much they know (whether it's fancy exercises, technical jargon, or special diets) rather than actually being effective at helping clients make the changes needed to move closer to their goals.*
*
I strive to help more people realize how much better their lives can be simply by making improvements that fit in their reality. I have to remind myself constantly to see things from the other person's perspectives so I can actually be effective. It's a work in progress. How can I help YOU?*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness*

caption:
Every Olympic weightlifting competition I participate in, I learn a little about myself. In my last competition in August, I learned about how lack of sleep affects digestion and fluid retention: When I weighed myself on the morning of the competition (since there are weight classes for competitors), I dropped over 3 lbs in a 24 hour period after finally being able to get a decent amount of sleep following many days of sleep deprivation. In the past couple months, I also learned how sleep deprivation (i.e. sleeping only 3 hours per night) is associated with very poor digestion, not to mention higher food cravings (salt in the wound!).
*
*
Sleep is so important. In the past, I sacrificed sleep to make sure I could do my gym training. Now, as much as I value exercise for health, I realize that sleeping those extra 2 hours would likely have contributed more to my health and sport performance than those 2 hours in the gym. *
*
Good health involves good exercise, good nutrition, AND good sleep and stress management. Are you getting all of these?
*
I also learned about the power of the mindset and sports nutrition: despite fasting for 24 hours before weighing-in for competition, I still managed to get a personal record by snatching 53 kg/117 lbs, 1 kg more than my previous record.
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz  #olympiclifting #weightlifting #vancouver #yvr #fitness

#ExerciseMinute: One easy way to get cardio exercise in any weather with NO equipment
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Bad weather stopping you from going outside to walk/run/hike? No treadmill next to your desk?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Cardio exercise doesn‚Äôt need to be limited to running or cardio machines. Body weight squats can be a great way to get your heart and breath rate up, and you can do them anywhere, anytime! Even better: Squats strengthen your leg muscles and bones more effectively. If you find them easy, here are some ways to make them more challenging:
‚Ä¢
1. Do more reps! If you‚Äôre not out of breath by 50 squats, you‚Äôre probably a Crossfit Games athlete. ‚Ä¢
2. Take 5-10 seconds to descend in every rep‚Äîbe ready for those thigh muscles to get gainz!
‚Ä¢
3. Hold the bottom of the squat for 5-10 seconds, using those muscles to maintain proper position. ‚Ä¢
Photo by @coachellen_ ‚Ä¢

caption:
Help wanted: Are you or do you know a care aide, nurse, community support worker, or other healthcare worker who struggles with staying fit and healthy? If so, I would love your advice‚Äîit will take just one minute. If you know somebody, please tag them below or share. Survey linked in my bio or at http://silviahua.com/healthcare-workers (or simply http://silviahua.com > click on ‚ÄúHealthcare Workers‚Äù)
*
TL; DR: I would like to get insight from care aides, nurses, community support workers, and other healthcare workers on the challenges they face in taking care of their own health and fitness.*
*
As our population ages and we face a shortage of these health care workers (https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/seniors-staffing-shortage-1.4720948), how can we keep patients and workers safe? I believe a key factor will involve addressing the barriers to worker health and fitness. While each individual should take responsibility for his/her own health, simply blaming individuals for not doing so does not help anyone. When your mother ends up in a care home, do you want a care aide who will be able to help keep her from falling, or one who lets your mother fall, as instructed by the employer, to avoid being injured herself (many employers do have such a policy)?*
*
In the occupational rehab program, I had many clients who worked as care aides, nurses, community support workers, and other hospital workers. Back and shoulder injuries from performing patient transfers are common in this group. Despite doing work that demands high physical and mental demands to keep patients safe, this group faces many challenges when it comes to health/fitness, including doing shift work, not having high income, having certain beliefs and attitudes about health/fitness/pain (most of these clients were immigrants and 99% are women), and of course, being in an environment that primarily focuses on being reactive rather than proactive when it comes to health.*
*
#nurse #careaide #hospital #carehome #fitness #yvr #vancouver #health #healthcare #nutrition #worksafe #worksafebc #wcb #workerscompensation

#MindSetMinute: Open your mind, change your palette
*
Did you know that your expectation on how a food will taste influences how you will experience eating the food?
*
People sometimes remark that my food choices are boring, likely because my meals are mostly vegetables and protein and super simple (my #LazyCookIdea hashtag is a clue). I think this is because people associate ‚Äúhealthy‚Äù with boring when it comes to food. *
*
Instead of expecting something to taste good or bad, approach eating with an open mind. Maybe you‚Äôll be surprised about how satisfying and delicious brussel sprouts, potatoes, cauliflower, or carrots can taste (even with not fried or covered in sauce/cheese!). *
*

caption:
#MindsetMinute
*
"Assumptions make an ASS out of U and ME".
*
Think of something you're working on but are feeling stuck on. What beliefs do you have about the situation and why you're stuck? Could you imagine a case where these beliefs do not hold true? How can you test these assumptions? *
Example of how to question a belief:
*
Belief: Cake is bad for you.
*
Cake is generally high in calories and sugar, low in nutrients, highly processed, and easy to overeat. *
However, in some scenarios, cake can beneficial: 
A) If you haven‚Äôt eaten for 6+ hours and are about to go for a hard workout, having some carbs from the cake will help you have a better workout and reduce the stress response on your body that would otherwise result from high-intensity exercise in a fasted state.
B) If you are celebrating your grandma‚Äôs 100th birthday and the family is having a special cake made by mom, being able to enjoy the cake and special occasion with your family will do your soul way more good than feeling deprived and left out. *
Of course, in general, having cake for lunch everyday instead of meat and veggies is still not ideal for health in most cases. But it is important to always reflect on how your ideas/beliefs are serving you and be open to other perspectives. *
To get other perspectives, consume information from a variety of sources. Talk to other people and even consider hiring a coach who specializes in the area of interest. *
#doyouevenlift #gainz #carbs #dessert #cake #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #fat #paleo

#LazyCookIdea: Baking eggs in parchment paper muffin cups.
*
Eggs and their cholesterol content have been given a bad reputation due to some misinformed recommendations by the American Heart Association in the 70s. Good news: the cholesterol in your food does not actually cause your blood cholesterol levels to worsen. This is because your liver makes cholesterol and will simply make more or less depending on how much you get from your diet.
*
*
That said, diet and lifestyle are still important for the health of your arteries. Even if dietary cholesterol may not be bad for health, SATURATED FAT (another type of fat found in animal products) consumption is one of many lifestyle factors which may affect blood cholesterol levels (though eating too little saturated fat is not ideal either). *
*
Should you limit egg consumption? This study compared prediabetic/diabetic men who consumed 12+ eggs/week with those who consumed <2 eggs/week over for 6 months, with a final follow-up 12 months after the start of the study. Conclusion: The high egg group showed no adverse changes in cardiometabolic markers compared with the low-egg group. *
*
Note for the nerds: 
1. From the Heart & Stroke Foundation site: "Dietary cholesterol ‚Äì found in meat, poultry, eggs and dairy products ‚Äì has less impact on increasing your blood cholesterol level. Foods that contain lots of saturated and trans fat are the true culprits."
2. If you look up eggs in the American Heart Association's encyclopedia, it cites that saturated fat is the concern with eggs, not the egg's cholesterol content.
*
*
Disclaimer: This post is meant for general educational purposes and not to be taken as medical advice.
*
*
#doyouevenlift #gainz #protein #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness #eggs #fat #keto

caption:
What do I do when I don‚Äôt feeling doing my gym training? I take things one step (and set) at a time. 
Before training: ‚ÄúI just have to get through this warmup routine.‚Äù Before a set: ‚ÄúI‚Äôll just do this one set, then I can stop if I really want.‚Äù After that set: ‚ÄúThat wasn‚Äôt so bad. Maybe just one more set, then I can stop.‚Äù Etc. etc. 
Sometimes, you really do need to be compassionate to yourself and rest more. Other times, you just need to tell yourself to be an adult and do things that are important even when you don‚Äôt feel like it, and know that things are often not as bad as they were in your head.
*
*

caption:
#LazyCookIdea: Cooking big hunks of protein in the slow cooker. 
Is cholesterol bad? Well, no. Cholesterol itself is a molecule that is part of every single cell in the body and forms many vital hormones. When it comes to cholesterol in you blood, HDL and LDL are actually like buses that travel throughout the bloodstream with passengers that include cholesterol/fat (e.g. triglycerides). To keep things simple, LDL (the ‚Äúbad‚Äù ones) are the buses that drop off cholesterol/fat from the liver to other cells in the body. They have an important job, but sometimes they crash into the curb and can cause road jams (i.e. plaques). HDL (the ‚Äúgood‚Äù ones) are the buses that pickup stranded cholesterol/fat in the blood and bring them back to the liver so they don‚Äôt create problems on the road.
‚àô
‚àô
So how do you improve your blood lipids, i.e. increase HDL, decrease LDL, and decrease triglycerides? I mentioned yesterday that it‚Äôs not about how much cholesterol you eat, though too much saturated fat can be a problem for some*. Saturated fat from the diet is only one factor. Other ways to keep your arteries healthy which may be even more important include:
- EXERCISE!
- Maintaining a healthy body composition (i.e. keep a trim waist; 6 pack optional).
- Eat lots of vegetables and fruit! Fiber also helps reduce blood cholesterol.
- Eat mostly whole foods that are nutrient-dense. Minimize processed food (pasta and bread are processed food, even if whole wheat!).
‚àô
‚àô
* Like your steak but concerned about the amount of saturated fat? Dietary saturated fat is only one factor that influences heart health. Your overall diet quality (e.g. whole foods and minimally processed fat vs. processed food/fat/oil), physical activity level, and overall health also are important.
‚àô
‚àô
#doyouevenlift #gainz #protein #nutrition #vancouver #yvr #fitness

caption:
Just 22 more responses until I reach my target number of responses for my Strong Women Survey--help me out? 
The Canadian Physical Activity Guidelines recommends:
- Muscle and bone strengthening activities 2+ days/week
- 150 minutes of moderate- to vigorous-intensity aerobic activity per week (~22 min/day). ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Are you getting the recommended amount of physical activity? I‚Äôm looking for women to answer a few short questions regarding their exercise habits. If you‚Äôre a woman, please take a minute to fill out the survey if you haven't yet. If not, please share so I can get the most comprehensive understanding possible. Link to the survey: http://ow.ly/Oxpt30iPRr6 (link in bio). ‚Ä¢
Why women only? I am simply targeting a niche for now, one that I can relate to the most and because women are less inclined to do resistance training. I do want all genders to be physically active. 
Some context about myself: I am a Kinesiologist with the provincial Association of Kinesiologists. I use exercise as ‚Äútreatment‚Äù for people with injuries and other conditions. I want a world where people do not need treatment for preventable conditions in the first place and a world where people can use their bodies to their full capacity for as long as possible. People who have talked to me in the past few years know that my overarching life goal is to get more people physically active. I believe that to have the biggest impact in this area, we need to understand what really drives human behavior and address the real barriers people face in becoming more physically active. 
Thanks to everyone who has already responded and/or shared!  #exercise #physicalactivity #health #fitness #women

caption:
Turkey, especially turkey breasts, can be even drier than chicken breasts. The trick to making lean poultry juicy is to brine them, i.e. soak them in a salt solution for several hours. I brined 3 turkey breasts in 4 tsp of salt with just enough water to cover.  The meat was nice and juicy once cooked! 
Unfortunately, I learned the hard way to not cook whole turkey breasts on top of broccoli florets. Turkey was still raw when the broccoli was done! (I didn't cut the meat before cooking to avoid the hassle.)
#DoYouEvenLift #veggies #gainz
